<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Lanqing: China to Reduce Trade Surplus in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAVOS, Switzerland, February 1 (Xinhua) -- China will move to
reduce its trade surplus in 1998, China's Vice Premier Li Lanqing
announced here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
To reduce trade surplus "will increase our capacity to
withstand the impact of currency realignment taking place in other
East Asian economies", Li said at a plenary session of the ongoing
annual meeting of the World Economic Forum.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the trade surplus of China was over 40 billion
U.S. dollars, with net capital inflows standing at 34 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
As a result, supply exceeded demand on the domestic foreign
exchange market, and the central bank had to buy
34.8-billion-dollar worth of foreign exchange to absorb the
surplus, he added.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, he said, China will improve the
competitiveness of its exports by optimizing export structure and
reducing cost through various kinds of hard work, but not by the
devaluation of Renminbi (RMB) Yuan.
</P>
<P>
"Even if the growth rate in our export might be somewhat
dented, we would still maintain the stability of exchange rate of
RMB," he stressed. "This is not only in our own interest but also
a contribution to the recovery of stability and confidence on the
Asian currency markets." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980202.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Lanqing: China's Economy in Steady Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAVOS, Switzerland, February 1 (Xinhua) -- China's economy has
been growing steadily since 1979, with an average GDP increase of
9.8 percent over the last 19 years, China's Vice Premier Li
Lanqing said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
China's economic goal is an eight percent increase in the
remaining three years of this century, Li told a plenary session
of an ongoing annual meeting of the World Economic Forum.
</P>
<P>
Talking of the future, Li said, "In the opening decade of the
next century, we shall maintain growth at seven percent."
</P>
<P>
"On that basis, we aim to modernize our economy through another
30 to 40 years of hard work, so that our people can enjoy a
standard of living comparable to that of middle-income developed
countries," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
