<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Turns 67 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin,
who has been frequently troubled by health problems, turned 67
Sunday and accepted congratulations from several cabinet leaders.
</P>
<P>
A group of cabinet members headed by Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin flew to the Rus presidential country residence outside
Moscow to congratulate Yeltsin on his birthday, reported the
Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, who was born in a peasant family in the village of
Butka in the Talitsa district of Sverdlovsk region, was elected
Russian president on June 12, 1991, the first president of the
country, which used to be a member of the former Soviet Union. He
was re-elected to the post on July 16, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin last Friday announced that he won't run for a third
term of the presidency in the year of 2000, saying he would not
violate the constitution by running again.
</P>
<P>
Russia's post-Soviet constitution limits a president's period
in office to two terms.
</P>
<P>
But top aides say Yeltsin could probably run again if he chose,
because he first took office in 1991, two years before the
constitution was adopted, and thus is serving his first full term
under that document. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
