<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Glaxo, SmithKline Plan Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 1 (Xinhua) - Britain's two leading drug
companies have announced plans for merger to create the world's
largest pharmaceutical company worth 100 billion pounds (160
billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The announcement at the weekend comes less than two weeks after
news that SmithKline was to join force with American Home
Products. That plan has now been abandoned.
</P>
<P>
If the merger between Glaxo Wellcome and SmithKline goes ahead,
the world's largest pharmaceutical company would have combined
annual revenues of 26.6 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement, the two said they were considering a deal
in which Glaxo Wellcome shareholders would own 59.5% of the equity
of the combined company and SmithKline shareholders would take the
remaining 40.5%.
</P>
<P>
The deal "represents a compelling strategic opportunity for
both companies to enhance their industry position," they said.
</P>
<P>
"A major and significant benefit of the proposed merger would
be the formation of the largest research and development
organization in the global healthcare industry," they added.
</P>
<P>
The new company would take almost 10% of the international
medicine market. This would be twice the amount of its nearest
rivals, Merck of the United States and Switzerland's Novartis.
</P>
<P>
Glaxo and SmithKline employ about 110,000 people altogether
worldwide and the announcement inevitably sparked fears among
staff of job losses.
</P>
<P>
"The combined company can eliminate 25% of duplicate costs,"
an observer here said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
