<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Lanqing: China to Make Various Efforts to Keep </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAVOS, Switzerland, February 1 (Xinhua) -- China will make
various efforts to keep its economic growth steady for the next
three years, China's Vice Premier Li Lanqing said here today.
</P>
<P>
"As stability has yet to be restored to the financial markets
in some Asian economies, many may have a question on China's
ability to achieve the goal of eight percent GDP growth in 1998.
To that my answer is positive," Li told a plenary session of the
ongoing annual meeting of the World Economic Forum.
</P>
<P>
He gave several reasons to support his stand:
</P>
<P>
- China will increase investment in priority sectors.
</P>
<P>
These include irrigation and water supply facilities and other
agricultural infrastructure, construction of railways, highways
and transport facilities in both urban and rural areas,
environmental protection projects, development of high-tech
industries, technological upgrading of enterprises, housing sector
development and the development of mid-western areas.
</P>
<P>
Li believes that the rise in investment will no doubt generate
an expansion in employment and consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
- China will tap the purchasing power dormant in the rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
One of the greatest assets underlining China's strong growth is
its huge market potentials in the countryside. With the steady
development of the rural economy, the farmers are growing rich,
driving up the demand for both consumer and capital goods.
</P>
<P>
Measures will be taken to channel merchandise more efficiently
into the rural market.
</P>
<P>
- China will continue to improve its investment environment to
enchance its attractiveness for foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Renminbi Yuan is already fully convertible under
the current account, and the average tariff rate for industrial
products will be brought down to 10 percent by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Starting from January 1, 1998, the Chinese government has
re-instituted tariff and tax waivers on equipment imports for
foreign investment projects.
</P>
<P>
- China will improve the competitiveness of Chinese exports by
optimizing export structure and reducing cost through various
kinds of hard work.
</P>
<P>
"Even if the growth rat in our export might be somewhat dented,
we would still maintain the stability of exchange rate of RMB," Li
stressed. "This is not only in our own interest but also a
contribution to the recovery of stability and confidence on the
Asian currency markets." 
</P>
</TEXT>
