<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMAFIN Approves $46 Million for Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The Commonwealth Africa
Investment Fund Limited (COMAFIN) has approved business ventures
totaling 46 million U.S. dollars over the past 18 months.
</P>
<P>
In an interveiw with the Zimbabwe News Agency Sunday, out-going
Managing Director of COMAFIN, Jeffrey Goddard said that there had
been encouraging progress regarding the investment fund of 63.5
million U.S. Dollars and further amounts will be raised in due
course from financial markets.
</P>
<P>
"We have a number of other projects where we have agreed, in
principle, to an investment, and we shall be reviewing their
progress and deciding on the level of our involvement," he said.
</P>
<P>
Besides other businesses which had been approved, COMAFIN was
looking at another eight businesses which had, in principle, been
cleared for investment.
</P>
<P>
Three new projects in mining, cultivation of grapes and
property development have been approved by the COMAFIN investment
committee with an investment of 14 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The fund's strategy is to help to develop the region by
investing in resource-based business, such as agri-business,
mining and tourism and in privately-financed infrastructural
projects, particularly in transport and telecommunication,
Goddard said.
</P>
<P>
"COMAFIN believes that the prospects for growth in African
countries are improving, and that, by encouraging the flow of
direct foreign investment, there is an immense potential in the
region which can be increasingly realised," he added.
</P>
<P>
COMAFIN was launched in 1996 with the purpose of contributing
to the economic development of commonwealth African countries by
providing risk capital for investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
