<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer Says, No Deal "on the Horizon" for Lewinsky </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Monica Lewinsky's lawyer
William Ginsburg said Sunday the American people are already tired
of allegations of an affair involving his client and President
Bill Clinton, predicting that Clinton will survive the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"It will go away, it will pass, the president will remain in
office," Ginsburg said Sunday on NBC's "Meet the Press."
</P>
<P>
Ginsburg said the drawn-out immunity talks between his office
and Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr are once again on hold.
</P>
<P>
A deal with Starr "is not... on the horizon," he said. "I don't
know if they are over. I know they have none ongoing."
</P>
<P>
Starr is investigating allegations that Clinton had an affair
with Ms. Lewinsky, a former White House intern, and asked her to
lie about it. Clinton has strongly denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
Ginsburg also denied that, with his talks with Starr making
little progress, he was now seeking collaboration with White House
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
But he said that if Clinton's attorneys filed a motion to
dismiss the grand jury investigation, "we would certainly look at
that motion, and assess whether or not we wanted to join it. It's
certainly a possibility."
</P>
<P>
"I certainly would like to see the grand jury proceeding shut
down," he said on "Fox News Sunday."
</P>
<P>
Ginsburg described the relationship between Clinton and Ms.
Lewinsky as that of "colleagues." He wouldn't respond to questions
about the alleged affair.
</P>
<P>
"The American people are tired of hearing about the president's
sex life," Ginsburg said. "I think the American people have
focused on the real issues, not the president's sex life."
</P>
<P>
Lewinsky plans to leave Washington this week to visit her
father in California, according to Ginsburg. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980202.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Azerbaijan Opposes Russian Military Presence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Azerbaijani President Heydar
Aliyev on Sunday expressed his dissatisfaction with the Russian
military presence in Georgia and Armenia, the Interfax news agency
reported from Baku, Azerbaijani capital.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to president of Radio Free Europe Thomas Dine, Aliyev
said "I oppose the presence of Russian military bases in Armenia
and Georgia and I protest against Russia's military union with
Armenia."
</P>
<P>
The Azerbaijani president noted that he had informed Russian
president Boris Yeltsin of his position at the CIS summit held in
Chisinau, Moldova, in October last year.
</P>
<P>
Strongly opposing the military cooperation between Russian and
Armenia, Aliyev pointed out that "Even if Russia acts as a
mediator in the settlement of the Armenian-Azerbaijani conflict,
it has no moral right to conclude an agreement on military
cooperation with Armenia."
</P>
<P>
According to Aliyev, modern offensive weapons worth one billion
U.S. dollars had been passed to Armenia "through Russian military
bases in Armenia and Georgia". "We have an exact list of weapons
passed to Armenia," he said.
</P>
<P>
Baku is urging Russia to confiscate these weapons from Armenia
and punish those involved in that deal, Interfax quoted Aliyev as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The president also reaffirmed Azerbajian's interest in
normalizing relations with Iran, noting "We are concerned about
Iran's intensive strategic cooperation with Armenia."
</P>
<P>
Russian Federation Council chairman Yegor Stroyev had a tour to
Azerbaijan on January 23, when he said that Moscow remains
committed to a peaceful settlement of Azerbaijan's territorial
integrity.
</P>
<P>
On the expediency of Russian military presence in Georgia and
Armenia, Stroyev noted that Russian bases in these countries will
never be used against Azerbaijan or any third country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
