<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice Premier Meets with EU Head </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAVOS, Switzerland, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier
Li Lanqing met here today with President of the European
Commission Jacques Santer.
</P>
<P>
During their talks at the occasion of the annual meeting of the
World Economic Forum, Li said that the relationship between China
and the members of the European Union (EU) have been well
developed.
</P>
<P>
Through high-level exchanges of visits and contacts, and active
political consultations and dialogues at different levels, Li
said, the cooperation of the two sides in all aspects has been
constantly broadened.
</P>
<P>
Both sides hold identical or similar views to many of the major
international issues, Li said. China and the EU are mutually
complementary in economy.
</P>
<P>
Santer said that the EU puts much emphasis on developing
relations with China and it admires China's great achievements
since its opening-up.
</P>
<P>
Li is pleased that the European Commission has made a proposal
to exclude China from its list of non-market economies. He
expressed hope that the proposal will be passed soon.
</P>
<P>
Santer said he is convinced that a positive solution will be
found as early as possible.
</P>
<P>
On China's entry into the World Trade Organization (WTO), Li
hoped that the EU would take a more flexible, practical and
constructive attitude to solving those suspending issues in order
to conclude the talks at an early date.
</P>
<P>
Santer reaffirmed that the EU supported for China's early entry
into the WTO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
