<DOCNO> XIE19980202.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Send Envoy to Iraq to Seek Solution to Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 1 (Xinhua) -- France will send the secretary
general of the French Foreign Ministry, Bertrand Dufourcq, to Iraq
within 48 hours to join the diplomatic efforts being made by
Russia in seeking a diplomatic solution to the confrontation
between Iraq and the United Nations over arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
The French Foreign Ministry said in a communique issued Sunday
that Dufourcq will carry a message from President Jacques Chirac
to Iraqi President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
"France wishes to warn Iraq against the risks which the
present situation carries and recall the principles of a
diplomatic solution which cannot be based other than on the
resolutions of the (U.N.) Security Councils," said the
communique.
</P>
<P>
The communique stressed that France would do everything to
"let a diplomatic solution prevail rapidly."
</P>
<P>
After making a telephone conversation with U.S. President Bill
Clinton on the situation in Iraq on Saturday, President Chirac
said that France would send "a firmest message to Iraq so that it
can measure the consequences of its refusal to cooperate with the
United Nations."
</P>
<P>
Russia is sending its vice foreign minister, Viktor
Possuvalyuk, to Baghdad in a new round of diplomatic efforts in
helping seek a diplomatic solution to the crisis, while Turkey
announced Sunday that it is also sending an envoy to Iraq.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
