<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Interior Minister Condemns U.S. Iraqi Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 1 (Xinhua) -- French Interior Minister
Jean-Pierre Chevenement Sunday strongly condemns the policy of the
United States toward Iraq, which he said is no longer a military
threat to any country.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the French media, Chevenement said that it
is "unimaginable" that France join a military intervention
against Iraq for its refusal to cooperate with the United Nations
arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
He described the strategy of the United States toward Iraq as
"prisoner of a kind of imbecile diabolizing (of Iraq) which is
already dated seven or eight years."
</P>
<P>
He said that as a result of this policy, one million Iraqis,
most of them children, could have died because of the economic
sanctions imposed on Iraq since its invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
"It is time to lift this ferocious embargo which has probably
led to one million deaths. It is absolutely dishonorable and I
hope that France would make its voice heard," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chevenement also warned that the blockade of the Mideast peace
process and a military intervention in Iraq will "nourish the
blaze of fundamentalism" in Muslim countries, particularly in
North Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said that France is more directly concerned about Islamic
extremism on the southern coast of the Mediterranean, while the
United States has its interests in the Mideast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
