<HEADLINE> Albright: U.S. Has Authority to Strike against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said on Sunday that the United States has the authority
to launch a military strike against Iraq without the need of a
fresh U.N. resolution for that move.
</P>
<P>
"We believe we have the authority for a strike," she told CNN
in an interview from Kuwait where she had just arrived to drum up
support for U.S. possible military actions from Gulf states.
</P>
<P>
She added the Clinton administration does not think it needs
the U.N. Security Council to pass a new resolution before the
United States can use military force against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Albright said the possible military strike may within weeks to
force Iraq to comply with U.N. resolutions on weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
"It's not days and it's not months, so that leaves weeks," she
told CNN about the time frame for the possible strike.
</P>
<P>
The United States prefers to find a diplomatic solution to the
standoff but "that string is running out," the secretary said,
adding "the time on it is shorter and shorter. But we are trying
still to work on a diplomatic solution."
</P>
<P>
Albright expressed confidence that the U.S. Congress would
support any military action taken against Iraq. But she said she
did not think "it's essential" for Congress to approve a
resolution supporting the action. 
</P>
