<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO to Celebrate Golden Jubilee of Multilateral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAVOS, Switzerland, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The World Trade
Organization (WTO) will celebrate the 50th anniversary of the
multilateral trading system on May 20, WTO Director-General
announced here today.
</P>
<P>
"This year is the golden jubilee of the multilateral trading
system," Ruggiero said in a statement issued on the occasion of
the ongoing annual meeting of the World Economic Forum.
</P>
<P>
"On May 20, 1998, we will hold a high profile celebration in
Geneva to mark the golden jubilee and highlight for the citizens
of the world the contribution this system has made to global peace
and prosperity."
</P>
<P>
On January 1, 1948, the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade
(GATT), signed by 23 nations on October 30, 1947 in Geneva,
entered into force.
</P>
<P>
GATT was later superseded by WTO which entered into force on
January 1, 1995.
</P>
<P>
"The creation of this system surely ranks among the greatest
economic achievements of the post-World War II era," Ruggiero
pointed out. "For a war-torn international community, the system
gave substance to a shared dream of a fair and open world trading
system."
</P>
<P>
"More than that, it has led directly to the breaking-down of
barriers not just between countries but between peoples," he went
on. "At the heart of the system is the principle of
non-discrimination."
</P>
<P>
"The multilateral trading system continues to grow in scope and
credibility," Ruggiero said. "Currently, there are 132 member
governments, with an additional 30 negotiating their terms of
membership. It would be difficult to overstate the contribution
the WTO makes to growth and development on a world scale." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980202.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CEOs of Computer Companies on Challenges of 21st Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAVOS, Switzerland, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Chief executive
officers (CEOs) from U.S. computer software and service companies
Monday discussed here challenges of the 21st century and how the
Internet will change our lives.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 1998 annual meeting of the World Economic Forum,
Bill Gates of Microsoft said that two keys to his company's success
were sharing wealth with employees to build a long-term relationship
that makes best use of their talents and working with partners.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Gates said, his company continuously monitored
what users needed and what competitors were producing in order to
gauge the opportunities and threats facing the business.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Microsoft had shared more wealth than
probably any other company by giving employees stock.
</P>
<P>
On strategies for the 21st century, Gates observed that
interaction costs have now dropped to almost zero. "We are sure
that information technology is changing the rules of the game. We
don't know how that is going to restructure business," he added.
</P>
<P>
Giving his vision of how the Internet will influence people's
lives, Stephen Case of America Online suggested that just as the
1960 U.S. election was said to have been decided by television, "the
next election could be decided on the Internet", because of the
intense involvement of users of the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
He noted that America Online had signed a final agreement to take
over CompuServe and become a business with 13 million customers.
</P>
<P>
Larry J. Ellison of Oracle observed that to have its full impact,
the Internet would need to be as easy to use as the telephone or
television and reach many more people.
</P>
<P>
Oracle and Microsoft now were involved in the production of more
simple machines to hook-up through the television.
</P>
<P>
When the Internet links become universal, Ellison said,
companies will be able to take advantage of instantaneous
information technologies not just in financial transactions but
also in labor, to commission work across the world, or in ordering
supplies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
