<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Minister Withdraws Resignation Request </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Deputy Defense
Minister Anuruddha Ratwatte Monday decided not to resign from his
post as deputy defense minister.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to President Chandrika Kumaratunga, Ratwatte
explained the reasons which led to his withdrawal of his
resignation appeal.
</P>
<P>
He said that due to the trust of the president and the
peace-loving people from all walks of life in Sri Lanka, as well
as his heavy duty to end terrorism and war in his country, he
decided to retain the post.
</P>
<P>
Ratwatte submitted his resignation letter to Kumaratunga last
Wednesday, saying he felt responsible for the serious security
lapse which led to the bomb attack at the Dalada Maligawa (Tooth
Relic Temple) in Kandy, some 115 kilometers east of Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Some rebels of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE)
detonated an explosives-laden truck on January 25, killing 17
people and damaging the temple, which is the holiest shrine to Sri
Lankan Buddhists.
</P>
<P>
The president in a letter dated January 29 requested the
minister to retrieve his resignation appeal.
</P>
<P>
Last week, people of different organizations held a string of
demonstrations in Sri Lanka, calling on Ratwatte, who also heads
the Irrigation and Power Ministry, to stay.  
</P>
</TEXT>
