<HEADLINE> Clinton Proposes $270.6 Billion Defense Budget For 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
on Monday proposed a 270.6 billion U.S. dollars military budget
for 1999, including 48.7 billion dollars for high-tech arms.
</P>
<P>
The planned military spending in the fiscal year beginning
October 1 is 3 billion dollars more than the current Pentagon
spending and represents a major slice of the 1.73 trillion dollars
federal budget sent to Congress by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Under the budget, the Pentagon planned to spend more on
procurement of such new weapons as 30 F-18E/F advanced fighter
jets, 66 Army "Apache Longbow" helicopters, two initial F-22
radar-avoiding "stealth" fighters for the 21st century and bigger
stockpiles of satellite-guided missiles and bombs.
</P>
<P>
Also included in the modern arms spending would be more than 2
billion dollars for Army "digital" equipment such as tiny
satellite receivers in the backpacks of soldiers to indicate their
exact positions.
</P>
<P>
The defense budget would also spend 600 million dollars on
protection against chemical or biological attacks, including on
protective clothing, detection devices and establishment of 10
highly trained "chem-bio" military teams to move about the United
States as needed in such emergencies.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 Clinton budget makes available a special 3 billion
dollars outside of regular defense allocations for U.S. troop
deployment in Bosnia beginning in October and military
humanitarian relief in emergencies.
</P>
<P>
But the outlays for the current U.S. military build-up in the
Gulf and for a continued American troop presence in Bosnia between
June and October of this year would be funded by special
supplemental requests to be sent by the Pentagon to Congress at
mid-year.
</P>
<P>
The combined Navy and Marine Corps would get the biggest slice
of 1999 defense spending authority at 81.3 billion dollars,
followed by 78.4 billion dollars for the Air Force, 65.2 billion
dollars for the Army and 37 billion dollars for other defense
agencies.
</P>
<P>
The new military budget includes nearly 4 billion dollars on
defense against missiles, including 300 million dollars for
development of an Air Force airborne laser that one day might be
used to burn up attacking warheads in flight.
</P>
<P>
To save money for modern weapons, the U.S. Defense Department
planned to cut 23,000 troops in fiscal 1999, bringing the active
duty armed forces down to 1.39 million troops, and close more
unnecessary bases that once used to house as many as 2.17 million
troops in the Cold War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
