<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. President Proposes New Budget Promising $9.5 Bln Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Monday submited to the Congress a 1.73 trillion U.S. dollar budget
proposal that could produce a 9.5 billion dollar surplus, the
first for three decades.
</P>
<P>
In addition to draw the prospect of the first federal budget
surplus since 1969, Clinton's plan proposes spending billions more
for such popular programs as child care, education and medical
research.
</P>
<P>
In his budget message, Clinton said his plan "brings to an end
three decades of fiscal chaos, a period in which Americans had
lost confidence in their government and the ability of their
leaders to do the people's business."
</P>
<P>
The 1999 budget, for the fiscal year beginning October 1, this
year proposes a 3.9 percent increase from this year's spending
levels with even bigger increases for scores of favored
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
The president's budget seeks to expand the federal government's
role in providing child care, lower the age limits for Medicare
and help hire 100,000 new teachers to reduce class sizes in the
nation's schools.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who promised during last week's State of the Union
address to produce budget surpluses for as "far as the eye can
see," would start the process with a 9.5 billion dollar surplus in
the next fiscal year. His budget document projects 1.1 trillion
dollars in surpluses over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
While Clinton would achieve surplus three years earlier than
the 2002 deadline set in last summer's balanced-budget agreement
with the Congress, he also wants to boost spending and pay for
that increase by raising taxes by 90 billion dollars, mainly on
tobacco and corporations.
</P>
<P>
Clinton would pay for his new initiatives with 24 billion
dollars in corporate tax increases and 65.5 billion dollars in
higher tobacco taxes, both stretched over five years. The latter
increase would come through enactment of a tobacco settlement that
faces an uphill battle in Congress.
</P>
<P>
Republicans said it was highly questionable for Clinton to
stake so much of his budget on a tobacco agreement uncertain of
ratification. But administration officials defended the spending
blueprint as a faithful effort to adhere to the guidelines
hammered out in last year's balanced-budget deal.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. recorded budget deficits that led to a fivefold
increase in the national debt from less than 1 trillion dollars
when former President Ronald Reagan took office in 1981 to 5.4
trillion dollars today.
</P>
<P>
While the budget deficit hit a record of 290 billion dollars in
1992, it has declined steadily since then, falling to a 23-year
low of 22 billion dollars last year as the strong economy produced
an unexpected flood of new tax revenues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
