<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat sent an envoy to Baghdad
Monday to show support for Iraq over the weapons inspection
crisis, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The report said Azzam Ahmad, who is holding the PNA portfolio
of public works, carried a message of support from Arafat to Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein. There is no confirmation from the PNA
side.
</P>
<P>
The message will also brief Saddam on the Sunday meeting held
between Arafat and United States Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright in the West Bank city of Ramallah, the report said.
</P>
<P>
At the news conference following her talks with Arafat on
Sunday, Albright acknowledged she had discussed the Iraqi crisis
with Arafat. In her words, Arafat called for Saddam's compliance
with all United Nations Security Council resolutions while he
mentioned about the difficulties Iraqi people face under the
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said Arafat had already sent a message to
Saddam via the Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) Ambassador
to Iraq "within the framework of attempts to find a peaceful
solution to the crisis and to try to prevent an explosion."
</P>
<P>
Albright is currently on an European and Middle East tour to
solicit support from the U.S. allies and Arab countries to the
U.S. plan on a possible military strike against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and his PLO strongly supported Saddam in the 1991 Gulf
War, thus alienating the PLO from the oil-rich Gulf states such as
Kuwait and Saudi Arabia, and resulting in the loss of huge
economic assistance.
</P>
<P>
Albright, meeting with Israeli and Palestinian leaders, was
trying to achieve progress in the Israeli-Palestinian peace
process so as to make it easier to rally support from Arab
states.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, however, has rejected Albright's idea to accept
Israel's proposal on gradual redeployment of troops from about 10
percent of the West Bank. 
</P>
