<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europe's Loan Risk From Asia Crisis Manageable: S&AMP;P </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 2 (Xinhua) -- European banks could face a loss
of up to 20 billion U.S. dollars on their lending to Asia,
according to the latest estimates of Standard &AMP; Poor's.
</P>
<P>
The estimation was based on calculation by the credit rating
agency on European bank credit exposure to four Asian countries
affected by the current economic crisis: South Korea, Thailand,
Indonesia and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
S&AMP;P expected that 20 of all European banks exposed to the Asian
turmoil may carry 85-90 percent of an exposure of 110-130 billion
dollars to the four Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
It estimated that 30 percent of the loans to Thailand and 50
percent of those to Indonesia would be "non-performing" in 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, S&AMP;P believed that European banks are strong enough to
weather the shock. "The potential damage is manageable in the
context of the capital strength and indeed the earnings capacity
of the European banking sector," the agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
