<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT, Febuary 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea's National Assembly (parliament) Monday
unanimously adopted a resolution, denouncing Japan's recent
scrapping of a bilateral fishery agreement.
</P>
<P>
"It is deeply regrettable that the Japanese government
unilaterally abolished the fishery agreement," said the
resolution.
</P>
<P>
The parliament said Japan should take full responsibility for
any possible incidents which would occur as a result of its
scrapping of the 1965 accord. (SKorea-Japan-Fishery Accord)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The British government has decided to send six navy
war planes to the Gulf region while the U.N.-Iraq standoff over
arms inspection continued worsening.
</P>
<P>
British government officials were quoted by BBC television as
saying Monday morning that six Sea Harrier jump jets left their
base at Yeovilton, southwest England, to the Mediterranean to join
the aircraft carrier Illustrious. (UK-Gulf)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan's foreign exchange reserves rose 736 million
U.S. dollars in January to 221.5 billion dollars, the Finance
Ministry said Monday.
</P>
<P>
In December, Japan's foreign exchange reserves had posted the
first fall in five months due to market intervention by Japanese
monetary authorities to halt the yen's drop against the
U.S. dollar. (Japan-Foreign Reserves)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DAVOS -- Vice President of the European Commission Sir Leon
Brittan said he was confident that China would be able to join the
World Trade Organization (WTO) in 1998 if the necessary momentum
in the negotiations were maintained.
</P>
<P>
"The message today is that we are prepared to move as quickly
as China on this matter," Brittan said at Sunday's plenary session
of the annual meeting of the World Economic Forum.
(Switzerland-China-WTO)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea had a trade surplus of 1.6 billion
U.S. dollars in January, the third month in a row despite the
country's serious financial crisis since last October.
</P>
<P>
Exports totaled 9.16 billion dollars in January, up 1.4 percent
over December, and imports were 7.56 billion dollars, down 39.6
percent, the Ministry of Trade, Industry and Energy said
Monday. (S. Korea-Trade Surplus) 
</P>
</TEXT>
