<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poverty in Zambia on Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's Central Statistical
Office has disclosed that the incidence of poverty in Zambia has
been decreasing steadily from 1993, Times of Zambia reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
People living in poverty in Zambia rose from 69.9 percent in
1991 to 73.8 percent in 1993 and decreased to 69.9 percent in
1996, according to a statement released in the capital Sunday by
the office.
</P>
<P>
David Diangamo, director of the office, said in the statement
that the steady decline in poverty is expected to continue.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the increase between 1992 and 1993 to the
initial implementation of the structural adjustment program which
resulted in a number of people being vulnerable due to
privatization and retrenchments.
</P>
<P>
Diangamo added that the other reason for the increase in
poverty is the severe drought which impoverished a number of
households.
</P>
<P>
He also disclosed that extreme poverty increased from 58.2
percent in 1991 to 60.6 percent in 1993 and steadily declined to
53.2 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The reduction in poverty levels is mainly due to the improved
performance of the informal sector where significant increase in
incomes has been recorded, explained Diangamo.
</P>
<P>
The director also attributed the reduction in poverty to the
shift by rural households from traditional low income crops to
cash crops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
