<HEADLINE> Germany's Ex-Minister Tries to Save German in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Former German Economics Minister
Juergen Moellemann is heading for Iran Monday to try to save a
German businessman from death penalty for having sexual relations
with a Moslem woman, the German Bild newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Moellemann is due to hold talks with Iranian government
representatives, trying to help the 56-year-old Hamburg
automobiles and textiles exporter, Helmut Hofer, who were
sentenced to death by an Iranian court a week ago.
</P>
<P>
Moellemann's trip was confirmed later Monday by German Foreign
Minister Klaus Kinkel at a news conference here. But he said the
former minister was not going to Tehran on behalf of the German
government.
</P>
<P>
Expressing his shock at the death sentence, Kinkel also
repeated his call for Hofer's release.
</P>
<P>
On speculations in the German press that there could be
political considerations behind the incidence, Kinkel said that he
did not have the impression that Tehran was attempting to strain
bilateral relations through the death sentence.
</P>
<P>
German-Iranian ties just recovered from a bitter dispute last
year after a German court ruled that Iranian leaders had ordered
the killings of four Kurdish dissidents in a Berlin restaurant in
1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
