<HEADLINE> Chinese Capital To Enrich Poor Farmers In Hilly Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Beijing, the Chinese capital,
has launched a three-year program to help enrich one million rural
people living in its remote hilly areas.
</P>
<P>
This is the fourth scheme of the city government to boost local
economic development in these areas through implementing
large-scale water conservation projects.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, each mountain resident will own 0.12 hectare
of irrigated farmlands by the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
In the hilly areas, which account for 60 percent of the city's
total, local farmers' yearly income is only half that of those who
live on the plain.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the city suffered from a severe drought. Local
authorities feared that the calamity might hinder development in
the hilly areas. However, the drought has become a driving force
for local farmers to build irrigation facilities.
</P>
<P>
The government program has allowed individuals to purchase,
contract, lease, sell, inherit and own small irrigation projects.
</P>
<P>
Individuals can also set up joint ventures with the government
to build the infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Some 130,000 hectares of farmlands will benefit from the
program, and the investment is expected to be recovered within two
years.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, local farmers have invested 18 million yuan in the
program, exceeding the sum invested by the government, for the
first time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
