<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Measles Cases Down Sharply in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The number of measles cases
decreased by 94 percent last January compared with the same period
in 1997, the Philippine Health Department said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Only 65 measles cases with no report of death were admitted at
the San Lazaro Hospital, the government referral center for
infectious diseases, last January, compared to 1,048 admissions
with 52 deaths in January 1997, the department said.
</P>
<P>
The low measles admissions last month surprised health experts
since the viral disease incidence peaks between January and April.
</P>
<P>
Health Secretary Carmencita Reodica attributed the drop to her
department's nationwide immunization program.
</P>
<P>
Reodica said routine anti-measles vaccination of all nine-month
old infants has been given free in all health facilities
nationwide since 1983.
</P>
<P>
"Vaccination is the most effective way of protecting our
children from measles considered a severe disease that kills about
3,000 Filipino children every year," the health chief said.
</P>
<P>
To prevent the high transmissibility of measles, she said, the
health department will launch a mass vaccination by September this
year to reach all children aged between nine months and 14 years.
</P>
<P>
"These are the main strategies to interrupt the transmission of
the disease," she said.
</P>
<P>
She further noted that most of the measles cases in 1997 were
unvaccinated and case fatality ratio was significantly higher for
those below nine months compared with those nine months or older.
</P>
<P>
Measles is highly contagious and it could reduce body
resistance and make a patient susceptible to more serious
complications such as pneumonia, otitis media, diarrhea and
encephalitis, which may cause death if not properly attended to.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
