<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's GDP Up in Third Quarter of 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The gross domestic product
(GDP) of Hong Kong had a robust, albeit somewhat decelerated,
growth of 5.7 percent in real terms over a year earlier, the local
Census and Statistics Department said Monday.
</P>
<P>
As to external trade in goods, re-exports increased by 4.2
percent in real terms from July to September 1997 against the
same period of the previous year. Meanwhile, domestic exports
recovered to a growth of 6 percent in real terms, arresting a
declining trend since the fourth quarter of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on these latest GDP figures, a local government
spokesman said growth of Hong Kong's economy was particularly
robust during the first three quarters of last year, especially in
the second quarter, with the GDP growth rate hitting the highest
since the third quarter of 1992.
</P>
<P>
However, he cautioned that a market slackening in growth was
likely to have occurred in the fourth quarter of 1997, as the
contagion effect of the regional financial turmoil spread to the
Hong Kong economy.
</P>
<P>
The preliminary estimates of Hong Kong's GDP for 1997 as a
whole are expected to be released on February 18.  
</P>
</TEXT>
