<HEADLINE> Saddam Meets Russian President's Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
Monday met with Russian President Boris Yeltsin's envoy Viktor
Posuvalyuk, who is on the second visit in a week to Baghdad to
find a peaceful solution to the Iraqi-U.S. standoff.
</P>
<P>
Posuvalyuk, who is also Russia's deputy foreign minister,
arrived here Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
He conveyed a verbal message from Yeltsin to Saddam with
respect to contacts made by Russia to find an appropriate
political solution to the "U.S. fabricated crisis," said the Iraqi
News Agency (INA).
</P>
<P>
Saddam expressed appreciation of the efforts being exerted by
the Russian president, and Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov,
emphasizing "the friendship and confidence ties linking Iraq and
Russia," according to INA.
</P>
<P>
INA said that it has been agreed that consultations would
continue between the two countries. No other detail is available
now.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Premier Tariq Aziz and Foreign Minister Mohammed
Saeed al-Sahhaf were present at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf said at a news conference Sunday that Iraq is dealing
with all diplomatic efforts in a constructive way, stressing that
diplomatic efforts is the way to defuse the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Iraq proposed last month to freeze discussions or actions
regarding U.N. arms inspectors' access to presidential sites until
results of the technical evaluation meetings, which are under way
in Baghdad, come out.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. rejected the Iraqi proposal and has threatened
military strike to force Iraqi compliance with relevant Security
Council resolutions, that is, unrestricted access to all suspected
sites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
