<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet, Once a Province of China in Yuan Dynasty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Scholar Wang Gui has
released the results of research showing that Tibet was a province
of China during the Yuan Dynasty (1271-1368).
</P>
<P>
Wang, an expert at Tibetan studies, said that the Yuan Dynasty
government established the Council of Buddhist Affairs to
administer Tibet, an area which at that time was known as Tubo
(Tufan), or ancient Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Wang pointed to the fact that various historical documents in
Tibetan and English clearly referred to Tibet as "Tibet (Tubo)
Province" or the "Province of Tibet (Tubo)", much as they would
refer to Sichuan and Shaanxi provinces.
</P>
<P>
He said that discoveries in the historical documents provide
convincing proof of China's sovereignty over Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Wang said he found the terms of "Tibet Province" and "the
Province of Tibet" mainly in "The Genealogy of Sagya", a classical
Tibetan work, and "The Travels of Marco Polo", the English version
on the life of the Italian explorer.
</P>
<P>
"The Genealogy of Sagya", which records relations between the
Yuan Dynasty and the Sagya Sect in ancient Tibet, says that
Emperor Kublai Khan governed 11 provinces. Tubo, the smallest
province in area, was the home of Grand Master Phatspa, and the
source of Buddhism in China.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that Marco Polo, who was guest of the Yuan Dynasty
court for 17 years, listed Tubo as a Chinese province in his book
entitled "The Travels of Marco Polo".
</P>
<P>
Wang said the English version of the book, published by the
Macmilan Company in 1927, contains the phrase "Province of Tibet",
on page 172. The phrase "the Province of Tibet" is included in
the version published by an American publishing house or the John
Publishing Company in New York in 1948 -- on page 100.
</P>
<P>
"It's interesting that the Tibetan and English books, all
considered highly authoritative historical records, share
identical points of view on the fact that Tibet was a Chinese
province during the Yuan Dynasty," said Wang.
</P>
<P>
Various Chinese historical documents show that the central
government of the Yuan Dynasty established 11 provinces to form
local governments, including the provinces of Lingbei, Liaoyang,
Henan, Shaanxi, Gansu, Jiangzhe, Jiangxi, Huguang, Sichuan,
Yunnan and Tibet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980202.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey to Mediate Over Iraqi Crisis: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- A Turkish official declared
here Monday that Iraq has accepted Turkey's proposal to mediate
on the crisis between the United States and Iraq over the arms
inspection.
</P>
<P>
Necati Utkan, spokesman for the Foreign Ministry, told a
weekly press conference that Turkey has got a confirmative
response from the Iraqi government to the peace initiative.
</P>
<P>
"Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem will go to Baghdad on a
mission aimed at contributing to a solution to the crisis," Utkan
said, declining to say whether a concrete plan has been prepared.
</P>
<P>
He did not reveal the exact date of Cem's trip to Iraq, just
saying that "the foreign minister will visit Baghdad in the coming
days."
</P>
<P>
He also said that Turkey welcomes the participation of other
neighboring countries of Iraq, such as Iran, Jordan as well as
Saudi Arabia, to the peace initiative.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's mediation proposal came after Iraq rejected a demand
from the U.S.-led United Nations arms inspection team that the
Iraqi presidential palace be checked for suspected weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
Utkan said that Turkey is firmly opposed to proliferation of
weapons of mass destruction in the region.
</P>
<P>
He, however, said that Turkey hopes that the confrontation
between Iraq and the United States could be solved through
peaceful and diplomatic means.
</P>
<P>
The sovereignty of Iraq and the well being of the Iraqi people
should also be taken into serious consideration at the same time,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz said that
Turkey would not take an active role in any military action
against Iraq and had reservations about participating passively.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the Turkish government is now also in
close contacts with the U.S. side on any new developments
regarding the Iraqi crisis.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the United States has not made a request of
using the Incirlik air base in southern Turkey for possible
military strike against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Incirlik air base was used by Western allies' warplanes to
launch air raids on Baghdad during the Gulf War following the
Iraqi invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
