<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Cocoa Export Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria recorded a drop in its
cocoa export between September and November last year, the vital
period of the 1997-98 harvest season, according to the Federal
Products Inspection Service (FPIS).
</P>
<P>
The cocoa harvest months in the country range from September
to March every year.
</P>
<P>
An FPIS report said total export in the three months under
review amounted to 29,514 tons, falling by at least 29,407 tons
from that registered a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The figures for December 1997 and January 1998 are yet to be
released, but exporters have given the indication of low trading
since the pre-Christmas period, the Business Concord reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
They said the December 1997 export would be lower than the
33,900 tons in the same month a year earlier as demand for
Nigeria cocoa was being discounted overseas.
</P>
<P>
However, larger volume is expected during this January-March
period as enough stockpile may have been effected during the
Christmas and New Year holidays.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports have projected lower production of 150,000 to
155,000 tons for the 1997-98 harvest season due to slow pace of
research that could have led to cultivation of new cocoa
plantations as the existing ones are aging. 
</P>
</TEXT>
