<HEADLINE> Air India to Cut Loss-Making International Routes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Air India facing with an
acute financial crisis has decided to discontinue many of its
existing loss-making international flight routes.
</P>
<P>
Managing Director of Air India M. P. Mascarenhas told a press
conference here Monday that his airline, India's international
flag carrier, would discontinue its services from Seoul of South
Korea where the airlines was incurring huge losses because of the
recent currency crisis affecting Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Services would also be suspended in Japan from where traffic
and earnings were going down because of a decrease in tourist
traffic and fluctuations of the yen, he said.
</P>
<P>
Air India services to South Africa would also be discontinued
because it is an uneconomic route, he further said.
</P>
<P>
The airline however would increase its services to the Gulf
region, to Chicago, the United States and Manchester, England, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Air India managing director said the currency crisis in
Southeast Asian countries and a fare war started by British
Airways had severely affected the working of his company, bringing
its losses to 1.02 billion rupees (27.2 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
