<HEADLINE> Dredging Project for Guangzhou Port to Start in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, February 2 (Xinhua) -- A project to dredge and
deepen the sea-bound channel of the Guangzhou Harbor has been
approved by the central government. Work is scheduled to begin in
June.
</P>
<P>
The project should be completed within two years and, by then,
vessels with a capacity of 50,000 dead-weight tonnage will be able
to sail into the Huangpu Port Block.
</P>
<P>
Huang Guosheng, director of the port administration, said that
the port, located in Guangzhou, capital of south China's Guangdong
Province, is the largest of its kind in south China. But the depth
of its sea-bound channel is insufficient to cope with growing
demands.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the ranking of the port regarding the handling volume
dropped to fourth in the country, compared with third in 1996,
though it handled 75 million tons of goods last year.
</P>
<P>
The dredging project will be carried out in two phases, with a
total investment of 1.5 billion yuan to be jointly financed by the
central, provincial and city governments.
</P>
<P>
The depth of the channel will be increased from the current
10.5 meters to 12.5 meters when the project is completed.
</P>
<P>
The completion of the project is expected to increase the
viability of the port, Huang said.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 the port handled 680,000 TEUs of containers, up 20
percent over the previous year, ranking sixth in the
country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
