<HEADLINE> Guangdong to Go Ahead with Poverty Alleviation Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Ou Guangyuan, vice-governor
of South China's Guangdong Province, said today that his province
will go on with its work of poverty alleviation, though absolute
poverty has been almost eradicated.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that by the end of 1997, 583,000 out of 600,000
poor people in the province earned more than 1,000 yuan (120
U.S. dollars) as the annual income, which enabled them to make a
living with enough food and clothing.
</P>
<P>
But 40 percent of these poor people, totalling 250,000, still
need help in maintaining their basic living standard, Ou said. The
province also bears the responsibility to help people living in
ethnic minority areas and under harsh natural conditions, he said.
</P>
<P>
The key point of Guangdong's poverty alleviation will shift to
improving the productive force and overall quality of farmers
through science and technology, Ou said.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government will continue to retain its poverty
relief funds and projects, infrastructure construction and
training courses for poverty-stricken areas, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
