<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Search for Missing Philippine Plane Suspended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Rescue operations for a missing
Philippine passenger plane carrying 104 people were suspended late
 Monday afternoon due to low visibility, rescue officials said.
</P>
<P>
Captain Christie Datu of the Philippine Air Force told
reporters that the Air Force suspended its rescue efforts at 5
p.m. local time due to poor weather conditions and low visibility.
</P>
<P>
He said the search operation will resume early Tuesday morning
and concentrate on a mountainous area northeast of Cagayan de Oro
City, the destination for the ill-fated Cebu-Pacific Air plane, on
the southern island of Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Datu said a helicopter pilot returning from the search mission
said he spotted the plane's wreckage while he was airborne over
Mount Kabantao, some 16 kilometers away from the Cagayan de Oro
City airport.
</P>
<P>
But Datu added that the report has yet to be verified since the
helicopter could not reach the suspected crash site due to the
stiff terrain.
</P>
<P>
Datu also ruled out a possible hijack of the DC-9 McDonnell
Douglas jet plane since no related radio communication was
received.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said all airports and cities near Cagayan de Oro
City had reported no landing of the plane, carrying 99 passengers,
including four foreigners, and five crew members.
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old aircraft, which took off from the Manila
Domestic Airport at 9:00 a.m. local time, was scheduled to land in
the Cagayan de Oro City airport, some 500 miles (800 kilometers)
south of Manila, at about 11:00 a.m.
</P>
<P>
But the plane made an unscheduled stopover in Tacloban City and
failed to arrive at the destination.
</P>
<P>
Air transport officials said the pilot of the aircraft, Captain
Paulo Justo, made a last radio contact 13 minutes before
approaching the runway of Cagayan de Oro City airport.
</P>
<P>
The plane had asked for an emergency landing about 60
kilometers away from the city.
</P>
<P>
The Cebu-Pacific Air, owned 49 percent by Filipino-Chinese
billionaire John Gokongwei, is one of several new airlines
established after the Philippine government deregulated the
aviation industry two and a half years ago.  
</P>
</TEXT>
