<HEADLINE> 78,000 Laid-Off Women Re-employed in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Women's federations in
Shanghai, China's biggest industrial city, have helped 78,000
laid-off female workers find jobs in the past four years, by
taking a series of measures.
</P>
<P>
Through lectures and artistic performances, women's federations
at various levels in Shanghai have worked to clear up social
discriminations against laid-off women and helped expand their
opportunities to find new jobs.
</P>
<P>
For example, Hu Shuhua, who had been laid off, opened a garment
business together with other women workers. And Wu Zizhong, who
also was laid off, found a new job as a hospital nurse.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, women's federations in Shanghai have opened
more than 200 training courses on such subjects as marketing and
accounting. A computer network was also established to help
laid-off female workers, especially those in older age groups.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the women's federations offered neighborhood
services such as snack bars, canteens and part-time domestic help
to absorb 4,500 laid-off women last year. 
</P>
