<HEADLINE> Albright Carries No Proposals to Arafat: PNA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) said Monday that U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright put up no formal proposals to the Palestinians on her
current tour in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
PNA Minister of Local Government and Municipal and Village
Affairs Saeb Erekat, in a telephone interview with Voice of Arabs
Radio from Jericho, said Albright "did not present any official
suggestions" to PNA President Yasser Arafat when they met Sunday
in the West Bank city of Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said that the two-hour talks between Arafat and Albright
last weekend dwelt on a series of ideas and details related to
endeavors exerted to put the peace march back on its normal track.
</P>
<P>
"Arafat underscored to Albright that the Palestinian stance is
based on the fact that Palestinians were ready to cooperate with
any quarter in order to implement signed agreements with Israelis
provided that no party departs from the framework or principles of
these agreements," he said.
</P>
<P>
Peacemaking between Israel and the Palestinians has been
blocked for almost a year, with the sides now deadlocked over the
issues of a long overdue Israeli troop pullback from the West Bank
and Palestinian steps to improve security.
</P>
<P>
Senior Palestinian and Israeli officials reported no movement
towards ending the stalemate as a result of Albright's visit.
</P>
<P>
Her visit followed separate talks U.S. President Bill Clinton
held with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Arafat in
Washington last month which also failed to narrow the gulf between
the sides.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has reportedly rejected Clinton's proposal of a phased
Israeli withdrawal and delaying the rest pullbacks until the
holding of the final status talks.
</P>
<P>
Albright, after her meeting with Arafat, said that Israeli and
Palestinian envoys would go to Washington next week to resume
talks on ways of pushing forward the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
In her press conference in Ramallah with Arafat, Albright said
U.S. efforts for reactivating the process achieved slight
progress, warning that the current stalemate of the peace process
has lasted for long enough.
</P>
<P>
Albright will fly to Egypt Tuesday morning for talks with
President Hosni Mubarak and Foreign Minister Amr Moussa during her
second visit here in just over a year as secretary of state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
