<HEADLINE> Ugandan Bank Sells Shares to Asian Buyers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- In a privatization drive,
Uganda Commercial Bank (UCB) sold 49 percent of its shares and
Westmont Land (Asia) Berhad, a Malaysian group, has paid some 10
million U.S. Dollars to acquire the shares.
</P>
<P>
The 49 percent of share-holding money of UCB was deposited in
the bank's account in Citibank, New York on January 27, 1998 by
the Malaysian International Financial Group, to the Ugandan
government, ''the New Vision'' reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian buyers had three months beginning last October
to pay 11 billion Uganda Shillings for UCB shares. The balance of
one billion Shillings will be paid within an extended period of a
month up to the end of March due to restriction resulted from
foreign exchange transfer in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
UCB is the largest commercial bank in the country. the Ugandan
government decided to sell part of its shares and privatize other
important state enterprises such as Uganda Electric Board and its
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The government will hold 51 percent of the shares of UCB.
</P>
<P>
Leonard Muganwa, the Executive Director of Enterprise
Development Project in the privatization unit, confirmed the
report and said the buyers will submit the names of their extra
staff to Bank of Uganda this month. ''They will begin operations
this month,'' Muganwa said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
