<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Accuses Japan's Fishery Accord Abolition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 2 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's National Assembly
(parliament) Monday unanimously adopted a resolution, denouncing
Japan's recent scrapping of a bilateral fishery agreement.
</P>
<P>
"It is deeply regrettable that the Japanese government
unilaterally abolished the fishery agreement," said the resolution.
</P>
<P>
The parliament said Japan should take full responsibility for
any possible incidents which would occur as a result of its
scrapping of the 1965 accord.
</P>
<P>
It urged the Japanese government to take a sincere attitude
toward future negotiations between the two countries on revisions
of the accord so that friendly relations could be maintained.
</P>
<P>
The parliament also urged the South Korean government to take
all possible measures, including the scrapping of its
self-regulation of the operation of South Korean fishing boats
near Japan's waters.
</P>
<P>
On January 23, Japan announced its decision to invalidate the
fishery pact after the two countries failed to reach a revised
treaty over fishing after 10 rounds of negotiations in the past
two years.
</P>
<P>
Revising the 1965 fishery pact has long been a thorny issue
between the two nations because they have to redraw their sea
boundaries under a U.N. maritime convention.
</P>
<P>
The pact stipulates that it will remain effective one year as
from the time one side notifies the other of its unilateral
invalidation of the pact. The one-year period is designed for
further talks for a revision of the pact. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
