<HEADLINE> China Plans to Increase Cultural Exchanges Overseas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 2 (Xinhua) -- China is planning to further
promote its cultural image abroad in a variety of ways, including
using the Internet.
</P>
<P>
According to a plan of the Culture Ministry, the country will
urge provinces and cities to join in cultural exchanges with
foreign countries, in addition to strengthening inter-governmental
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
A program introducing China's 5,000-year-old culture on the
Internet is planned, and channels for promoting commercial
performances and exhibitions abroad will be created.
</P>
<P>
However, cultural activities that might degrade the country's
dignity will be banned, according to the plan.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Chinese musicians staged a folk concert in
Vienna, raising the curtain for many international cultural events
with China playing the leading role, including the China
International Fine Arts Year and China International Vocal Music
Contest.
</P>
<P>
The Culture Ministry is planning to stage art festivals in
South Africa, the Middle East and Spain; hold an exhibition in the
United States; and take part in the Asian Art Festival this year.
</P>
<P>
China's increasingly active cultural role in the international
arena has been in proportion to its robust economy and rising
international status, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
The Culture Ministry plan also includes more exchanges with the
Hong Kong SAR (Special Administrative Region), Macao and Taiwan.
</P>
</TEXT>
