<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Have More Private Phone Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's deregulation
(decentralization) of the telecommunications sector will go
further ahead this week, with five more private telephone firms
expected to start operation.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian newspaper reported Monday that the independent
telephone network is already connected to the network of the
state-owned Nigerian Telecommunications Limited (NITEL).
</P>
<P>
Four others, namely, the Em-International Systems Limited,
Intercellular Nigeria Limited, Mobitel Limited and Communications
Infrastructure Limited is now at the point of interconnection,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
The five companies will be providing 45,000 digital lines in
the Lagos area in the beginning and have the capacity of 280,000
lines in the future, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's liberalization of the telecommunications sector
started with the introduction of decree 75 in 1992, which breaks
the monopoly of the NITEL and encourages private investment in
the sector.
</P>
<P>
The liberalization process took the first solid step two
months ago, with the formal operation of 10,000 digital lines by
the private multi-links telecommunications limited. 
</P>
