<HEADLINE> US Increases Investment in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States has put
more investment in South Africa since the latter abolished
apartheid in 1994, local Business Report quoted an American
research institute as reporting Monday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. presence in South Africa has surpassed the investment
levels of U.S. firms in the early 1980s, Peter De Simone, leader
of the Investor Responsibility Research Center (IRRC), said.
</P>
<P>
The number of U.S. companies with investments in South Africa
has almost tripled from 104 in 1991 to 296 today, according to
the IRRC.
</P>
<P>
SBC Communications, the largest single U.S. investor so far, paid
757 million U.S. Dollars last year for a 30 percent stake in Telkom,
South Africa's parastatal telephone company.
</P>
<P>
Another newcomer to South Africa is McDonald's, which was forced
to wage a copyright fight against a local company which had taken
the same name under apartheid.
</P>
<P>
These newcomers, as well as returnee such as Dow Chemical, have
pushed the level of assets held by U.S. companies to an all-time
high, more than three times in real terms what they held in the
early 1980s, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
