<HEADLINE> Tourist Arrivals to Macao Drop 14.1 Percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Tourist arrivals to Macao reached
seven million last year, down 14.1 percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the Macao Census and Statistics Department
Monday show that a total of 7,000,370 tourists arrived in Macao in
1997.
</P>
<P>
While the number of passengers from Taiwan increased 19.5
percent, those from Japan, Southeast Asia, the Republic of Korea,
Australia, North and South Americas, Europe and Hong Kong all
dropped.
</P>
<P>
The number of passengers coming from or via Hong Kong declined
20 percent from that in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The largest drop was from Japan, down 43.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Local Analysts say that the decline of arrivals was the result
of the currency crisis in Southeast Asia, the less tourist
arrivals to Hong Kong and a rising crime rate in Macao.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is a leading sector of the economy in Macao, which has
a population of 415,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
