<HEADLINE> South Korea's Overseas Construction Orders Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 2 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's construction firms
won overseas contracts valued at 102 million U.S. dollars in
January, accounting for only 10.1 percent of the same month last
year.
</P>
<P>
The International Contractors Association of Korea said Monday
that the country's construction firms set a record last year by
receiving orders amounting to 14.03 billion dollars from abroad.
</P>
<P>
The association attributed the decrease to the current
financial crisis sweeping South Korea and Southeast Asian
countries which are the major markets for South Korean builders.
</P>
<P>
Among January's construction contracts are five new
small-amount orders from Mexico, the Philippines, Laos, Tanzania
and Britain.
</P>
<P>
The Southeast Asian countries, suffering from financial problem
resulting from sharp devaluation of their currencies against the
U.S. dollar, have been reducing their infrastructure projects
since late last year.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to make up for the declining orders from the
Southeast Asian countries, South Korean builders are exploring new
markets such as Central and South America and Africa, where they
had paid little attention in the past.
</P>
<P>
They are also seeking orders from the Middle East, once the
largest market for South Korean firms in the late 1970s and early
1980s.
</P>
<P>
South Korea predicted last month that this year's overseas
construction order receipts will decline by about 30 percent to 10
billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
