<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ferrara's Operation Set to be Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Surgeons will not do a rush
operation on Ciro Ferrara with a hope to save the Italy and
Juventus defender to compete in the World Cup finals this summer.
</P>
<P>
Ferrara broke both bones in his leg in a tackle during Sunday's
league game at Lecce and was due for an operation on Monday.
</P>
<P>
But surgeons at the Turin clinic are now expected to wait until
Tuesday, to allow time for swelling to go down.
</P>
<P>
The most optimistic outcome is that Ferrara will be out for
three months -- taking him through to early May. He will then be
able to start training with Juventus.
</P>
<P>
However, it leaves him precious little time to reach match
fitness again, and even less for him to get a few games under his
belt before the Italian squad leave for France.
</P>
<P>
The finals start on June 10, with Italy turning out on June 11
against Chile in Bordeaux.
</P>
<P>
Italy's coach Cesare Maldini said: "It's terrible. Let's just
hope that Ferrara gets fully fit again as soon as possible, for
his benefit rather than the national team's."
</P>
<P>
It would not be the first time, though, that Ferrara missed a
major event.
</P>
<P>
An abdomenal injury shortly beforehand cost him the 1996
European championships, and a torn thigh muscle meant he missed
Italy's 0-0 draw with England last October in their last World
Cup qualifying game. 
</P>
</TEXT>
