<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Market Urged to Open to Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni asked for a mutual beneficial globalization of world
economy in Davos Economic Summit, Switzerland, local media
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The globalization is not new to Africa, but it is connected
with slavery, imperialism and colonialism in the continent in the
past, the president said.
</P>
<P>
What Africa wants now is mutual beneficial globalization, the
president underlined.
</P>
<P>
Some constraints hindering development of African economies
must be removed, Museveni said, referring to problems Africa are
faced with, including inadequate infrastructure, low numbers of
entrepreneurs, inadequate scientific research, debt burden and
agricultural modernization.
</P>
<P>
Africa cannot be intergrated into world economy without
addressing these problems, local media quoted the president as
saying.
</P>
<P>
President Yoweri Museveni was backed by Jerry Rawlings, the
head of state of Ghana, and Daniel Duncan, the Prime Minister of
Cote d'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
Jerry Rawlings and Daniel Duncan asked last Saturday for
access to European markets for a smooth globalization, reports
reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
President Museveni also met with Newt Gingrich, the speaker of
the United States' house of representative, and Chilean president
Eduardo Fei.
</P>
<P>
Museveni discussed with Gingrich promotion of U.S. investment
and infrastructure development in Uganda. Gingrich informed
Museveni that the U.S. congress is backing the Africa trade bill
which will soon be forwarded to President Bill Clinton for final
approval.
</P>
<P>
Museveni and his Chilean counterpart discussed ways of
cooperation to use Chilean expertise in food processing to help
build up and promote food industry in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents agreed the two sides will issue a joint
communique on cooperation through their diplomatic
representatives in Washington.
</P>
<P>
A Chilean technical team will visit Uganda to lay the ground
work for improving processing foods including fish and fruits.
</P>
</TEXT>
