<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Plays Key Role in Social Sector: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, February 2 (Xinhua) -- World Bank President James
Wolfensohn said here Monday that the World Bank is paying special
attention to the social impact the current financial crisis has on
the regional economies and that a balance should be achieved
between financial and social restructuring.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters at a press conference that the purpose of his
current tour in the region is to follow through on those parts of
analysis and restructuring programs that are for the bank to do.
</P>
<P>
They are essentially in two parts, he said. The first is to
follow up on where the government is requested in the
restructuring and strengthening of the financial system and the
capital market.
</P>
<P>
On the other side, very significantly, he said, the bank has
played a key role in working on the social sector.
</P>
<P>
"It is to the social program the bank pays very special
attention," he said, adding that it is a primary function of the
bank to deal with the issues of poverty alleviation and
environment and social issues which, he said, "are our major
thrust".
</P>
<P>
He said that it is for that reason that the World Bank is
directing its attention on two sides of the issue and his
discussions here were to try to get a better understanding of both
the impact on the finance sector and also observations on the
social side.
</P>
<P>
He also said that during his meeting with Asia's trade union
leaders here, they expressed their fears that rising unemployment
resulting from the region's financial crisis will unleash social
havoc for troubled economies.
</P>
<P>
There were concerns that jobs are being lost and that in most
of the countries there is very little social underpinning, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
He gave the news conference after meeting with Prime Minister
Goh Chok Tong and Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong earlier in
the day. Wolfensohn arrived in Singapore Sunday as part of a
week-long tour of Southeast Asia, including Thailand, Indonesia,
the Philippines and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
He also met with Finance Minister Richard Hu Sunday evening. He
said these meetings, along with extensive works by the World Bank,
revealed that the social impact of unemployment was already being
"vigorously and immediately felt".  
</P>
</TEXT>
