<HEADLINE> US Prefers Iraqi Changing Course: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States prefers
that the Iraqi President Saddam Hussein changes his course to a
diplomatic solution of the current crisis over the U.N. arms
inspection, the U.S. State Department spokesman said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
James Rubin told Xinhua at the Kuwaiti Airport before leaving
for Saudi Arabia that "We will prefer to see Saddam Hussein change
course and accept the requirements of the United Nations and allow
the inspectors to do their job, so that the threat of weapons of
mass destruction can be eliminated."
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been refusing to allow the U.N. arms inspectors to
enter sensitive places, including presidential palaces, where the
inspectors suspect chemical and biological weapons are hidden.
</P>
<P>
"If that (changing course) doesn't happen, we will not rule out
our options and we will do what is necessary to destroy its
ability to acquire and use weapons of mass destruction," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that "as far as the prospect of diplomacy working, we
will open to that possibility."
</P>
<P>
Rubin was accompanying the U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright on her Middle East tour to line up support for a
possible American strike against Iraqi targets.
</P>
<P>
Albright, wrapping up her two-day visit in Kuwait, left for
Saudi Arabia Monday to continue her tour which has already taken
her to Jerusalem and will further take her to Bahrain and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said "Albright was encouraged by her meeting with
Kuwaiti Emir last night and felt that the United States and
Kuwait are united in their determination to see Saddam Hussein
comply with U.N. and give up his weapons of mass destruction."
</P>
<P>
He said Albright and the U.S. Secretary of Defense William
Cohen have made clear that if diplomatic efforts fail to bring
any result, the "use of force would be substantial."
</P>
<P>
Referring the word "substantial," he said that this time "the
attacks would certainly be much more different" from what was
done before.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. was not able to convince Gulf countries of the need
for military reprisals when Iraq triggered the crisis by
expelling U.S. experts working with U.N. Special Commission on
eliminating weapons of mass destruction in Iraq last November.
</P>
</TEXT>
