<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Shrugs off Bad Trade Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar
shouldered worse-than-expected trade figures to close higher
Monday, boosted by a strong rally on the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The local currency finished at 68.19 U.S. cents, up from 67.01
U.S. cents here late Friday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. funds propelled the local currency nearly two U.S. cents
in New York Friday night, to a high of 68.80 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar consolidated its offshore rally in Sydney
Monday morning, only to be knocked back temporarily by news of an
880 million Australian dollars (598.4 million U.S. dollars)
deficit in the balance on goods and services in December.
</P>
<P>
Economists' forecasts for the balance on goods and services had
varied widely, from a surplus of 400 million Australian dollars
(272 million U.S. dollars) to a deficit of 650 million Australian
dollars (442 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Colonial State Bank foreign exchange dealer Nick Volanakis said
it was a bad figure for the Australian dollar, and the market
reacted by selling the currency.
</P>
<P>
The local currency dipped below 68 U.S. cents following the
release, but had regained the lost territory by the close.
</P>
<P>
"Aussie is in a very positive light considering how far it's
bounced since Friday night," he said.
</P>
<P>
"A lot of chartists are talking of a high up towards 69 to
69.50 U.S. cents," he added.
</P>
<P>
But Bankers Trust chief economist Chris Caton said the trade
figures would be interpreted by as many as the first sign of an
Asian effect, and thus may bring the recent rally in the currency
to a halt.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was at 86.19 Japanese yen, up from 85.40
locally Friday.
</P>
<P>
It also was at 1.2506 German marks from 1.2266.  
</P>
</TEXT>
