<HEADLINE> Brittan Confident China to Join WTO in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAVOS, Switzerland, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Vice President of
the European Commission Sir Leon Brittan said he was confident
that China would be able to join the World Trade Organization
(WTO) in 1998 if the necessary momentum in the negotiations were
maintained.
</P>
<P>
"The message today is that we are prepared to move as quickly
as China on this matter," Brittan said at Sunday's plenary session
of the annual meeting of the World Economic Forum.
</P>
<P>
Brittan made the comment after China's Vice Premier Li Lanqing
said at the same session that China "will not add fuel to the
flames" at the time of the Asian crisis by devaluing its currency
Renminbi Yuan to keep its competitiveness in exports.
</P>
<P>
Li told the session that China, besides keeping RMB stable, has
offered help and will offer more help to its Asian neighbors to
tide them over the unprecedented crisis.
</P>
<P>
Brittan listed several principles under which China's accession
to the world trade body could be accelerated.
</P>
<P>
"China's membership of the WTO is not meant to be a benefit or
a favor only to China," he said. "The membership will offer China
a transparent, binding set of rules. By joining the WTO, the
country will receive assured, legal access to the world market."
</P>
</TEXT>
