<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Promises to Continue Fishery Talks With South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Japan's decision to nullify a
fishery agreement with South Korea is aimed to speed up the
revision of the document, the Japanese embassy here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The underlying meaning of the notification to put an end (to
the fishery agreement) is to set a timetable to conclude the
fishery talks as soon as possible," said an embassy statement.
</P>
<P>
The two nations failed to reach consensus on revising the
agreement in 10 rounds of negotiations over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
On January 23, one day after Japan's decision to abolish the
pact, the South Korean government announced that it would take
retaliatory measures against the unilateral decision.
</P>
<P>
All South Korean political parties issued strongly-worded
statements accusing Japan of hurting the Seoul-Tokyo relations.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese embassy urged South Korea to be cool-headed over
the move, adding that the Japanese government will vigorously push
ahead with talks this year to reach an agreement on the revision.
</P>
<P>
The current fishery pact, signed in 1965, provides that it will
remain effective one year from the time one side notifies the
other of its unilateral invalidation of the pact.
</P>
<P>
The one-year period is designed for further talks for a
revision of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Revising the fishery pact has been a long-time headache of the
two countries as they have to redraw their sea boundaries under a
new United Nations maritime convention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
