<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea's Monthly Trade Surplus Hit 1.6 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 2 (Xinhua) -- South Korea had a trade surplus
of 1.6 billion U.S. dollars in January, the third month in a row
despite the country's serious financial crisis since last October.
</P>
<P>
Exports totaled 9.16 billion dollars in January, up 1.4 percent
over December, and imports were 7.56 billion dollars, down 39.6
percent, the Ministry of Trade, Industry and Energy said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus marks a high monthly improvement over the
deficit of 3.48 billion dollars in the same month a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the recent surplus to a nationwide gold
donation drive leading to gold export worth 580 million dollars
and to South Korean won's sharp devaluation depressing the imports.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, once the world's 11th largest economy, badly needs
foreign currency to tide over the crisis caused by the collapse of
some big conglomerates and bad loans of financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The nation has to pay back a large part of its external debts,
which total 153 billion dollars this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980202.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Prepares for War: Top Officer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Preparation for war is a
priority for Israeli Army in the new year, a top army officer has
said.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Chief of Staff Shaul Mofaz said, in an interview
published on the English daily The Jerusalem Post Monday, that
Israeli army will focus on increasing training, procuring more
weapons and replenishing stocks to prepare for a possible war.
</P>
<P>
As part of such preparation, the army has earmarked 150
million shekels (43 million U.S. dollars) for protecting its
troops in South Lebanon, which is the last active war front for
Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Air Force acquired recently two advanced American-made
F-15I fighter planes which increased Israel's far-distance air
striking capability.
</P>
<P>
Mofaz maintained that Israeli troops should be prepared for a
deterioration of the situation which could possibly leads to war.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli Defense Force is preparing for the possibility of
a conflict. This doesn't mean that there will be a war, or that we
have any signs that one is imminent. Our assessment says that it
is best to prepare from a starting point of the possibility of a
deterioration."
</P>
<P>
Mofaz said that in the post-Oslo Accord years, it was felt that
war was far off and there was a window of opportunity that allowed
more investment in research and development. But the window now is
smaller and a radical change came last fall when army intelligence
assessed that Syrian troop's redeployment and their enhanced
training was a sign of a higher probability of war, he said.
</P>
<P>
Some of the new weapons expected to be acquired in 1998 include
more F-15I and F-16 fighter planes, Black Hawk and Apache
helicopters, and Merkava III tanks. More units will also be set up
to take the burden off reservists.
</P>
<P>
But Mofaz complained that the approved 1998 budget of 32.6
billion shekels (9.31 billion dollars) for the army falls far short
of needs and the annual working plan has thus been modified.
</P>
<P>
The cut harmed the army's ability to maintain sufficient
supplies, training and better preparation, he added. "Anyone who
harms the conditions of the standing army weakens the army in the
long range," he warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
