<HEADLINE> Hun Sen Ignores Boycott of Elections by Opposition Parties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's Second Prime
Minister Hun Sen said he would not take into consideration any of
his opponents' boycott plan towards the country's next elections.
</P>
<P>
"Up to now, there are 42 political parties, if 10 of those will
not take part in the polls, there remains 32 others to run up in
the polls," Hun Sen told reporters during a local event.
</P>
<P>
It's normal for one or two parties to stay away from the
elections, but whenever they know there might be a victory, they
surely will step up to the polls scheduled for July 26, he said.
</P>
<P>
His remarks came one day after prominent opposition leader Sam
Rainsy made a statement urging all of his party's allies in the
Union of Cambodian Democrats (UCD) to block the general elections.
</P>
<P>
Besides Sam Rainsy's Khmer Nations Party (KNP), the UCD groups
Prince Norodom Ranariddh's royalist FUNCINPEC party, Son Sann's
Buddhist Liberal Democratic Party (BLDP) and Khmer Neutral Party.
</P>
<P>
The UCD was formed after the bloody event in early July last
year, when Prince Ranariddh, son of King Norodom Sihanouk, was
ousted by Hun Sen from his post as the first prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Japan has made a proposal to the two sides for
settling their conflict by peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
To Ranariddh, who has been in exile, the proposal calls for
cutting off relations of his resistant forces to those of Khmer
Rouge group and then integrating into the government's control.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, to Hun Sen, it calls for quick proceeding in the
criminial trial of the accused prince, with the granting of
amnesty by the King immediately after a possible verdict.
</P>
<P>
In essence, it urges Hun Sen, who is to discuss the matter with
the Japanese ambassador to Thailand, to secure the prince's safe
return to Cambodia and free participation in political activities.
</P>
<P>
As a latest development, Hun Sen was quoted by a government
official as telling the Thai ambassador here Monday that he will
not go to Thailand unless Bangkok does not play a mediation role.
</P>
<P>
In late January, Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai reportedly
invited Hun Sen for a visit to Thailand to discuss "bilateral
cooperation."  
</P>
</TEXT>
