<HEADLINE> New Philippine Cabinet Members Sworn In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
 Monday swore into office seven newly appointed Cabinet members,
who replaced those having resigned to run in the May 11 general
elections.
</P>
<P>
The reorganization was the last major revamp of the Cabinet
before Ramos steps down on June 30 when his six-year term ends.
</P>
<P>
All the seven appointments were in acting capacity except for
former assistant secretary Renato Corona who will be taking over
the post of chief presidential legal counsel vacated by Renato
Cayetano.
</P>
<P>
Among the new appointees are former budget secretary Salvador
Enriquez as acting finance secretary and former solicitor general
Silvestre Bello as acting justice secretary.
</P>
<P>
Under the Election Law, former finance secretary Roberto de
Ocampo, former justice secretary Teofisto Guingona and some other
former Cabinet members resigned earlier in order to run for
senatorial posts in the May general polls.  
</P>
