<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines, Slovenia to Expand Trade Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines and Slovenia
have signed an agreement to expand bilateral trade and economic
relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Agreement on Trade and Economic Cooperation between the two
countries was signed here on December 5, 1997 and ratified by
President Fidel Ramos Monday, a news release from the
Presidential Palace said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the two countries will give each other the
most-favored nation treatment for products originating from their
respective territories, the release said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will encourage the two countries, following the
international agreements and their respective laws and
regulations, to render each other assistance in organizing fairs,
specialized exhibitions and promotional campaigns.
</P>
<P>
It also exempts each country from customs duties and other
charges on the import of promotion materials, free samples of
products obtained at competitions, exhibitions and other
festivities and goods and equipment for fairs and exhibitions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
