<HEADLINE> Livingstone Council to Lay Off Half its Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Linvingstone city council of
Zambia will lay off half of its 800 workers this year because the
local authority can sustain the size, Zambia Daily Mail reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper quoted Abraham Mutakila, President of
Zambia United Local Authoritiese Workers Union (ZULAWU), as
saying in the southern city of Zambia Sunday that the union and
the council management have agreed to declare half of the work
force redundant.
</P>
<P>
This will enable the council to only remain with essential
workers it could afford to pay, he told hundreds of the council
workers.
</P>
<P>
The redundancies will involve every one including those in
management because they do not want to have a top heavy
arrangement.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that it is pointless for a council to have 800
workers whom it could not afford to maintain, adding that most of
the workers have become a burden to the council.
</P>
<P>
Some of the workers have not been paid their salaries for six
months, according to him.
</P>
<P>
He said it is better for people to be home and do other things
instead of working for a master who cannot pay them.
</P>
<P>
The council owes everyone money such that they do not even
know how to pay the debt.
</P>
<P>
Among those to be retrenched at the council are those who have
not yet worked for 10 years and those who often go on sick leave,
Mutakila said.
</P>
<P>
Ndola city council in the north of the country has intended to
off-load 100 workers every month until the 2,100 worker force is
reduced to 1,000, Times of Zambia reported last week.
</P>
<P>
In another northern city of Kitwe, council town clerk Ali
Simwinga said a retrenchment exercise targetingese 1,000
employees will start as soon as the funds are available.
</P>
<P>
Last week Finance Minister Ronald Penza said in his budget
report it is clear that the current number of public service
workers cannot be adequately supported by Zambia's economic base
and reinvigorating the process of a public service reform will be
a priority of the economic reform program in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
