<DOCNO> XIE19980202.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel-Egypt Trade Under Pressure, Report Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Israel's exports to Egypt
declined in 1997 due to the stalemate in the Middle East peace
process and other political reasons, local newspaper The Jerusalem
Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Israeli Federation of Chambers of Commerce
as saying that Israel's exports to Egypt dropped 5.3 percent last
year to 54.82 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
"There wasn't a single trade delegation from Egypt last year,"
and there were very few visits from Egyptian businessmen, said
Mandy Barak, head of the federation's international department.
</P>
<P>
Economic relations with Egypt began stagnating after the
arrest in late 1996 of Israeli textile worker Azzam Azzam, and the
detention in Cairo last summer of Israeli business-woman Dvora
Ganani, Barak noted. Cairo claimed both cases involved espionage.
</P>
<P>
According to Barak, the Egyptian government issued an order
that importers must show documents proving that Israeli products
are not produced in the occupied territories or the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
"This scared many importers, and is yet another barrier to
trade, " he said. "There are people who are afraid to go there to
make new contacts and deals. "
</P>
<P>
However, Egyptian Ambassador Mohammed Bassiouny to Israel
denied Sunday his government is doing anything to discourage
business with Israel. He said all Israelis are welcome to do
business in Egypt, "as long as they respect the law."
</P>
<P>
He contended that the Egyptian-Israeli trade stagnated in 1997
due to the political atmosphere, after years in which trade volume
doubled annually.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is one of the two Arab countries that have signed peace
accord with Israel. The other is Jordan.
</P>
<P>
"Trade expansion has stopped because there is a stalemate in
the Middle East peace process," he said. "The private sector is
affected by the political situation and the peace process."
</P>
<P>
"There is a big difference between peace and the fruits of
peace," Bassiouny said. "When Egypt made peace with Israel, we did
not aim at a separate peace. It was the first step at a
comprehensive peace. Economic relations will be much better under
the umbrella of comprehensive peace. "
</P>
<P>
Bassiouny said cooperation with Israel in agriculture is going
well, and Egypt is supplying Israel with around 20 percent of its
crude oil.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel's trade with other Arab countries has also
been declining, Barak said, with exports to Tunisia dropping 88
percent in 1997 to less than 500,000 dollars, and to Morocco by
21.9 percent to 4.8 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
