<HEADLINE> Philippine Passenger Plane Missing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Air Transportation
Office said Monday a domestic passenger plane was officially
declared missing after it failed to land at a local airport in the
southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching the office said the Cebu-Pacific Airways DC-9
jet plane's pilot captain Paolo Justo made a last radio contact 13
minutes before approaching the runway of Cagayan de Oro City
Airport.
</P>
<P>
The office said the passenger plane failed to land in its
destination Cagayan de Oro City, capital of Misamis Oriental
province in the northern tip of Mindanao Island.
</P>
<P>
The office said that the aircraft could have crashed in
Mindanao Sea south of the island.
</P>
<P>
Diego Garrido, spokesman of the Cebu-Pacific Airways, said that
the plane carried 99 passengers, including four foreigners, and
five crew members.
</P>
<P>
But he refused to give the names and nationality of the four
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old plane, which took off from Manila at 9:30 a.m.
local time from the Manila Domestic Airport, had asked for a
priority landing about 60 kilometers away from the city.
</P>
<P>
The plane was supposed to arrive at the city at between 11 a.m.
and 11:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Jose Mendoza of the Philippine Air Force said rescue
helicopters were sent to search for the missing plane.
</P>
<P>
The Cebu-Pacific Airways is a domestic airlines owned by
Filipino-Chinese billionaire John Guokongwei. 
</P>
