<HEADLINE> Kuwait Backs US Position on Iraqi Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait has said it fully
backs the position of the United States on the current crisis over
arms inspection in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
This stance came in a statement issued after the talks between
the visiting U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and
Kuwaiti Emir Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah here Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, Kuwaiti State Minister for Cabinet Affairs
and acting Foreign Minister Abdul Aziz Dakhil Al Dakhil said
Kuwait supports the firm position of the U.S. on forcing Iraq to
respect U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin
said Kuwait agreed with the United States that Iraq's lack of
cooperation with the U.N. weapons inspectors can not be accepted.
</P>
<P>
"Kuwait agreed one hundred percent with the secretary
(Albright)'s belief that (Iraqi President) Saddam Hussein's
continued obstruction of UNSCOM (U.N. Special Commission on
dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction) is unacceptable
and must stop," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
Albright arrived in Kuwait earlier Sunday within a new Middle
East tour to line up support for a possible U.S. military strike
against Iraqi targets.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been refusing to allow U.N. arms inspectors to search
sensitive places where the UNSCOM suspect chemical and biological
weapons are hidden.
</P>
<P>
Albright said the U.S. beefed up its military presence in the
region within a policy of "diplomacy backed up by force" and warned
that military action will be "substantial."
</P>
<P>
She also said the U.S. is one hundred percent committed to the
security of Kuwait against any possible attack by Iraq. 
</P>
