<HEADLINE> Kenya's Major Highway Closed Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The road between port Mombasa
and capital Nairobi has been closed to all traffic once more
after the Thange Bridge collapsed under the force of raging flood
water, the East African Standard reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The closure of the road which is considered as the country's
life line, comes barely two weeks after the swollen Kambu River
swept away its bridge on January 16 at Kibwezi, about 160
kilometers southeast of Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
The daily newspaper quoted Samson Akute, chief engineer of the
Ministry of Public Works, as saying Sunday that the section is
normally dry but following the El Nino rains, sudden springs from
Kyulu hills have brought down water, leading to excessive erosion
of the road.
</P>
<P>
Personnel from the Kenya Army and the Ministry of Public Works
were at the site trying to erect a temporary bridge for light
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Makueni District Works Officer Julius Mbevi told local
reporters that the temporary bridge would enable vehicles and
people to cross the section as from Monday.
</P>
<P>
A 20-foot-deep dam has formed at the Thange bridge as a result
of a cave-in of the culvert bridge following heavy rains in the
past three months, hampering repair work at the bridge.
</P>
<P>
The Mombasa-Nairobi road is a vital section linking Mombasa
port with sections of the hinterland in Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania,
Rwanda, Burundi and the eastern part of the Democratic Republic
of Congo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
