<HEADLINE> Lesotho Ruling Party Elected Honorary Life Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho Premier Ntsu
Mokhehle was elected honorary life president of the ruling
Lesotho Congress for Democracy (LCD) Sunday despite his request
to be relieved of the leadership position.
</P>
<P>
Local daily the Citizen said Monday that more than 1,300
delegates at the party's first annual general meeting in Maseru
also re-elected Pakalitha Mosisili as Mokhehle's deputy and chose
a new national executive committee.
</P>
<P>
Mokhehle, 79, did not attend the weekend party conference due
to a recent minor operation in Bloemfontein, South Africa. He
told South African Press Association earlier that he would not be
standing for being re-elected for the premiership of Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
The ailing Mokhehle, in a speech read on his behalf at the
start of the two-day LCD conference, asked delegates to relieve
him of party leadership duties, saying, "my body cannot carry me
anymore."
</P>
<P>
The LCD was formed in June last year after a protracted
leadership battle between pro-Mokhehle supporters and another
faction in the prime minister's former ruling Basutoland Congress
Party (BCP).
</P>
<P>
According to LCD Deputy Secretary-General Monyane Moleleki,
his party was registering 30,000 new members monthly since its
inception in June last year, adding that membership currently
stood at 200,000 card-carrying members.
</P>
<P>
The BCP failed to come up with an amicable solution and the
matter ended up in the country's high court, but it still
remained unresolved, prompting Mokhehle and his supporters to
resign from the party and form the LCD.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the formation of a new party, Mokhehle transferred
governance to the LCD, much to the dissatisfaction of his
opponents.
</P>
<P>
He was accused of "toppling" his own government, and Lesotho's
King Letsie III was asked to intervene, but the king refused,
saying he was not asked to do so by the government.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho's opposition parties formed an alliance against
Mokhehle and demonstrated against his moves for several months.
</P>
</TEXT>
