<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Govt in Bid to Stop Price Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government is
trying to stop price hikes by setting up a task force to ensure
ordinary people are not exploited, Minister of Industry and
Commerce Nathan Shamuyarira said Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
"The government is trying to hold prices where they are, so
that they don't shoot up unnecessarily. The government has to
see that ordinary people are not exploited or left in a situation
where basics are not in their reach," he told the Zimbabwe
Broadcast Company.
</P>
<P>
The government was doing its best to see to it that the social
unrest seen last month was not repeated, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government was going to put its house in order by reducing
the budget deficit by as much as it could which has already
dropped to seven percent from 10 percent, to improve the export
drive and industrialize quickly.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question on whether the government had blamed
anyone for the recent food riots, the minister said, "We cannot
blame either the government or the private sector. It's not a
matter of apportioning blame... What we should do is find causes
for the social unrest."
</P>
<P>
From January 19 to 21, thousands of people in Harare and other
small towns staged demonstrations in protest against steep price
increases. Some of them looted shops, stoned cars and destroyed
buildings, causing million of Dollars' losses.
</P>
<P>
"Don't be too negative in the efforts of the government and
the nation, we are doing our best," the minister said, adding the
government wanted to build comradeship among the Zimbabwean
people and integrate the private and public sectors, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
