<HEADLINE> Peace Seems to Hold in Angola, UN Peace-keeper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Commander of Zimbabwe's U.N.
peace-keeping army in Angola Godfrey Nyanda said here that the
situation in Angola is generally calm.
</P>
<P>
"It looks like peace is holding. There are indications that
permanent peace will soon be achieved in Angola," said Nyanda,
who returned home from Angola with a contingent of 66 soldiers
Sunday at the end of their three-month term of peace-keeping
duty.
</P>
<P>
He said there were no incidents of fighting at present, adding
that there was cooperation between the Angolan government and
Jonas Savimbi's National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
"The United Nations observer mission in Angola is doing its
best to ensure that lasting peace is achieved in Angola," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the last batch of about 80 Zimbabwean troops still in
Angola was expected home at the end of this week.
</P>
<P>
He said he was happy that all his men had returned home
safely. 
</P>
