<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealanders Urged to Save </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Jenny Shipley
Monday urged New Zealanders to save more to help their country
through a period of economic uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
Shipley was quoted by the local newspaper The Evening Post as
saying that she hoped New Zealanders would use the tax cuts in
July this year as an opportunity to save more.
</P>
<P>
She noted that the government would continue to run budget
surpluses, but individuals needed to reduce their debt as well.
</P>
<P>
She also echoed the view expressed by Reserve Bank Governor Don
Brash last week that increasing savings by New Zealanders was the
key to cutting New Zealand's current account deficit.
</P>
<P>
The current account deficit, measuring what New Zealand spends
and earns overseas, rose to 6.2 billion dollars (3.6 billion U.S.
dollars) in the year ending last September. New Zealand ranked
among the highest in term of deficit ratio to GDP in the OECD
member countries.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, the international credit rating agency Moody's
downgraded New Zealand's credit rating from stable to negative
because of concerns about the big deficit and the impact of Asian
economic crisis on the New Zealand economy.
</P>
<P>
But Shipley said earlier on television that New Zealand was now
 in a better position to deal with shocks like the Asian crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
