<HEADLINE> Tourist Industry Grows in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam received more than 1.7
million foreign tourist in 1997, an increase of 6.75 percent from
that of the previous year, the English-language daily "Vietnam
News" reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by the National Administration for Tourism
(VNAT) show that 40 percent of the total came on holidays while
23 percent visited the country for business purpose.
</P>
<P>
China's mainland topped the 1997 list of foreign tourist
arrivals with 405,389, followed by Taiwan with 15,068.
</P>
<P>
Last year, around 8.5 million Vietnamese travellers took
holiday tours, an increase of 30.8 percent compared with that of
1996.
</P>
<P>
1997 saw a drop in foreign investment in the tourism industry
with only 16 projects worth 369 million U.S.dollars being
approved, compared with 25 projects worth 1,04 billion dollars in
1996.
</P>
<P>
To attract more foreign tourists, Vietnam is considering to
take some "urgent" measures including new marketing campaigns,
endeavors to simplify visa formalities, better management of
travel agencies and the opening of border gates for Chinese
travellers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
