<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Currency Devalued Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's currency of taka has
been devalued against the US dollar by 0.85 taka, effective from
February 2, Bangladesh Bank (BB) said.
</P>
<P>
The new buying and selling rates of the dollar have been fixed
at 46.15 and 46.45 taka respectively, the central bank announced
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The rates were last readjusted downward at 45.30 and 45.60 taka
against the dollar on November 24 last year from 44.85 and 45.15
taka.
</P>
<P>
The adjustment is pursuant to the continuing policy objective
of maintaining incentives for exports and for inflows from
expatriate Bangladeshis, keeping in view the unfolding trends of
currency values of trade partners and competitors of Bangladesh,"
the BB said.
</P>
<P>
The taka has been devalued 12 times since the Awami League took
office in June 1996. It was devalued four times in the second six
months of 1996 and seven times in 1997. There had been more than
6.3 percent devaluation of taka in 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
