<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Howard: Any Change to Republic to Weaken Australia's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister John Howard
opened the Constitutional Convention Monday with a warning that
any change to a republic would weaken Australia's system of
government.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech to the convention, Howard said he
remained opposed to Australia becoming a republic because the
present system had provided "the rules for governing the nation
with both certainty and stability."
</P>
<P>
He told the 152 delegates gathering in the old Parliament House
that "I oppose Australia becoming a republic because I do not
believe that the alternatives so far canvassed will deliver a
better system of government than the one we currently have."
</P>
<P>
He said a modern government was most workable when the
ceremonial functions of government were separated from executive
responsibilities, with a politically neutral head of state.
</P>
<P>
However, Howard promised to put the republic issue to a
referendum in time for a change by the centenary of federation on
January 1, 2001, if the convention came up with clear support for
a particular model.
</P>
<P>
While at the same stage, Opposition leader Kim Beazley said,
the architects of Australia's constitution had set a republican
agenda which should now be completed.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Labor Party told the 152 delegates gathering in
the old parliament house that he would prefer an Australian head
of state to be elected by a two-thirds majority of a joint sitting
of both houses of parliament.
</P>
<P>
Beazley called again for the issue to be put to a public vote
as soon as possible, "In my view, Australians have long understood
the issues, we can take this opportunity to give those issues a
final push forward, then we must give Australians their say."
</P>
</TEXT>
