<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soaring Prices in Thailand Contributes to Fragrant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Unscrupulous Thai rice traders
are found mixing low-grade rice into fragrant rice sold in local
supermarkets, the Bangkok Post reports Monday.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources admit that top-grade rice has been gradually
disappearing from store shelves and is being replaced with
low-grade rice packed in bags labeled as Hom Mali (fragrant) rice.
</P>
<P>
Housewives also complain that they pay high prices for
top-quality fragrant rice, but when the rice is cooked, the usual
soft and tender texture and fragrant taste are absent.
</P>
<P>
Rice trading sources admit that the rising prices of fragrant
rice, now at 2,650 baht (50 US dollars) for a 100-kg sack, is "too
tempting".
</P>
<P>
Growing demand of fragrant rice from foreign markets has pushed
fragrant rice prices up considerably, with exports prices now at
about 750-760 dollars per ton, compared with about 450 dollars two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
Even though the Commerce Ministry has set standards to
guarantee the quality of fragrant rice exports, rampant
adulteration continues as the program is voluntary. It is not
mandatory for all rice traders to apply for the quality
certification and labeling.
</P>
<P>
To date, the ministry has granted the top-quality label to nine
companies under 11 brand names.
</P>
<P>
Under the labeling program, introduced since January 1, a bag
of first-grade fragrant rice must contain no more than 5 percent
of other lower grades and 0.04 percent of other mixtures, and that
at least 60 percent of the grains must be at least seven
millimeters long.
</P>
<P>
The label can be revoked if products are found failing to meet
the standards.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
