<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll Shows Clinton Ratings Higher Than Ever </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 1 (Xinhua) -- A nationwide Los Angeles
Times poll shows U.S. President Bill Clinton's job approval rating
is higher than ever, while more than one-third of respondents hold
a low opinion of his accusers in the latest White House scandal.
</P>
<P>
The poll, which surveyed 1,314 U.S. adults by telephone January
29-31, showed 58 percent believe allegations against Clinton have
more to do with partisan politics than "getting to the truth."
</P>
<P>
A record-high 68 percent of those polled said they approve of
the job Clinton is doing, while 29 percent said they disapproved.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 37 percent said they disapprove of the job being
done by independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr. Thirty-two percent
said they approved, while 31 percent said they weren't sure.
</P>
<P>
A contributing factor to Clinton's rising approval rating is
public perception that his private behavior doesn't affect how he
conducts official business.
</P>
<P>
While 42 percent said they believed Clinton had sex with intern
Monica Lewinsky, 45 percent said they don't believe he urged her
to lie about it. Seventy percent also said they believe Clinton is
a decent person with some character flaws.
</P>
<P>
The poll has a sampling error of plus or minus 3 percentage
points.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
