<HEADLINE> Household Appliance Purchases Rise in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Some 52 percent of the families in
Italy owned video recorders in 1996 as against 8.5 percent in
1987, a research institute said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The household possession of personal computers rose from 5.6
percent to 11.6 percent in 1996, the government-funded research
body Svimez said.
</P>
<P>
Nationally, 79.8 percent of the households had one car and
those with more than one climbed from 19.4 percent 1987 to 26.9
percent in 1996, the study said.
</P>
<P>
The cellular telephone, which came from zero possession in
Italy in 1987, rose to 9.5 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
But the households possessing motor scooters and motorbikes
were down from 24.9 percent to 22.3 percent two years ago.
</P>
<P>
The Svimez study said Italy is now saturated with such consumer
items as televisions, refrigerators and washing machines. 
</P>
