<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Workers to Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's 600,000 strong
workforce in tea and rubber estates have decided to stage a
nation-wide strike on February 5 following a breakdown in talks
with the Employers' Federation of Ceylon (EFC) over a wage hike.
</P>
<P>
Trade unions of the workers said Monday that the strike will
continue indefinitely till their demand is met.
</P>
<P>
The unions want the 23 management companies under the EFC to
raise the daily salary for workers from 83 Rupees (1.34 U.S.
dollars) to 103 Rupees (1.66 dollars). However, the EFC only
agrees to offer 93 Rupees (1.5 dollars).
</P>
<P>
EFC Secretary General Franklyn Amarasekera said Monday the
strike would adversely affect the industry and the country.
</P>
<P>
The last strike by estate workers in April 1996, which lasted
for one week, was estimated to have cost the government 500
million Rupees (8.1 million dollars).  
</P>
