<HEADLINE> Bangkok Airport Expansion Costs Too Much: Board </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's national planning
board disagrees with the 6-billion baht (110 million US dollar)
plan for the expansion of the Bangkok International Airport,
according to the Bangkok Post Monday.
</P>
<P>
A source from the National Economic and Social Development
Board said the board considers most of the expansion plan
unnecessary because the current regional economic crisis will
reduce air traffic volumes significantly at least for the next
five years.
</P>
<P>
The former Thai administration approved a budget of 11.69
billion baht for the expansion of the Bangkok airport and delayed
the construction of the second Bangkok international airport
because of economic constraints.
</P>
<P>
The current government reduced the expansion budget to 6
billion baht for the construction of a new control tower, new
office building and new parking lots, and improvement of domestic
and international terminals, runways and piers.
</P>
<P>
The board feels that at the present stage only 2 billion baht
is needed to relieve the bottleneck of traffic lanes in front of
the airport gates.
</P>
<P>
An obvious wastes of money in the expansion plan is the
construction of a new air traffic control tower. The new tower was
proposed only because trees in an adjacent golf course are
blocking the vision of the existing tower.
</P>
<P>
A simple and economical way to clear the problem is to close
the golf course and cut down the trees, as a gold course is a
violation of both security and safety standards of any airport,
the newspaper quotes the source as saying.  
</P>
</TEXT>
