<HEADLINE> U.S. Asks for Italy's Diplomatic Support in Iraqi Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright urged Italy to add its weight to diplomatic efforts to
resolve the current Iraqi crisis, the Italian Foreign Ministry
said in a communique issued Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
The communique said that Albright phoned Italian Foreign
Minister Lamberto Dini Sunday afternoon and explained the
United States' position regarding the Iraqi crisis and its plans
to resolve it.
</P>
<P>
Albright called Dini from Israel. She is on a European and
Middle East tour aimed at garnering support for a coordinated
effort to pressure Iraq into removing its block on United Nations
arms inspectors there.
</P>
<P>
In her conversation with Dini, the U.S. secretary of state
urged that efforts to resolve the crisis should be stepped up and
asked Italy to take part in a diplomatic drive to this end.
</P>
<P>
Dini told Albright that Italy would do its part, the communique
said.
</P>
<P>
Albright did not ask for permission to use Italian air bases in
the eventuality of military action against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministry said later that following his conversation
with Albright, Dini sent a letter to Iraqi Deputy Premier Tareq
Aziz.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said the letter had two objectives: firstly to
suggest ways of reducing tensions and overcoming the present
crisis, and secondly, to express hope that in the wake of the
crisis iraq and the international community would be able to
develop their relations.
</P>
<P>
Also today, Dini received a letter from Russian Foreign
Minister Yevgeny Primakov, who echoed Albright in expressing deep
concern over the situation and stressing that for the moment all
options remained open. 
</P>
</TEXT>
