<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Seen to Incur Huge Public Sector Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' consolidated
public sector position is expected to incur a deficit of up to
12.9 billion pesos (300 million U.S. dollars) in 1998 due to
persisting high interest rates and an estimated weak budget
surplus.
</P>
<P>
The consolidated public sector (CPS) position, a key fiscal
barometer, includes the cash positions of the government, the
monitored government-owned and controlled corporations and the
local government units.
</P>
<P>
The CPS is estimated to have a deficit of between 10 and 15
billion pesos in 1997, local newspaper the Business Daily said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted officials at the Development Budget
Coordination Committee as saying the biggest impact on the CPS
this year was the scaling down of the fiscal surplus target from
16 billion pesos to only 1 billion pesos for 1998.
</P>
<P>
The government earlier revised its originally quite ambitious
fiscal surplus target for 1998 to take into account continuing
revenue shortfalls and increased expenditures due to the current
currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
The committee also expressed concern that the government's weak
fiscal position could continue to pressure interest rates to rise
further this year as it might be forced to resort to compete with
the private sector for domestic loans.
</P>
<P>
The government's weak fiscal position is also one major concern
of the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
An IMF team is set to arrive here Wednesday to review the
country's economic fundamentals and compliance with the structural
reforms prescribed by the IMF for the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The review will determine whether the country deserves to exit
from the IMF's economic supervision gracefully and enter into a
"precautionary arrangement" to protect it from the current crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980202.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
