<HEADLINE> Italy Opposes Military Actions Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Italy opposes United States-led
military actions in Iraq and would not offer its air-bases for use
in any such operations, military experts here said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Rome's position is that a military attack would fail to produce
"decisive results" in Iraq, the experts said, adding that Italy
shares France's line that a further effort is needed to achieve a
diplomatic solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
These remarks were made after Italian Defense Minister
Beniamino Andreatta's statement on the previous day.
</P>
<P>
Andreatta told journalists Saturday that "the winds of war are
still some distance away," and Iraq still has several days in
which it could satisfy U.N. demands on the blocked arms
inspections.
</P>
<P>
Also on Saturday, Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini urged
a further push in diplomatic efforts to resolve the crisis over
U.N. arms inspectors in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"Not all the diplomatic avenues have been fully explored yet,"
he said, "even though recent developments have created a situation
of grave difficulty in Iraq."
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
reaffirmed in Jerusalem the American position that if diplomacy
proved unable to resolve the crisis, "the U.S. response would be
rapid and substantial." 
</P>
