<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: NZ Feels Bite of Asian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The ongoing Asian economic
crisis has begun to bite into New Zealand's economy, whose growth
is now increasingly dependent on Asia.
</P>
<P>
With six of its ten largest trading partners being in Asia,
about 40 percent of NZ's trade is conducted with the region.
</P>
<P>
Export is the first sector to be hit by the Asian crisis.
Latest figures released by Statistics New Zealand showed that
total exports in November 1997 fell by 4.4 percent compared with
the same month one year ago, with exports to Asia slumping by 10
percent and exports to Japan, South Korea and Indonesia all
dropping considerably.
</P>
<P>
Forestry also reported a big fall in export. South Korea, one
of the major buyers of New Zealand timber in Asia, has stopped
importing logs from NZ because business people have found it hard
to get letters of credit from banks.
</P>
<P>
The NZ forest giants, Fletcher Forests and Carter Holt Harvey,
now seem to be at a loss as how to deal with their huge log
stocks, some of which are still left unshipped at sea ports.
Fletcher Forests is reportedly considering to stop cutting trees
if the situation is not improved in South Korea, which bought
about half of NZ log exports before the financial crisis started
in that country.
</P>
<P>
NZ Dairy Board and Meat Board suffered similar losses in doing
business with Asia.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is also crying for help from the government. With
visitor numbers diving 90 percent from South Korea alone, many
tour operators said they could not sustain the losses. The number
of tourists from Southeast Asian countries also dropped
drastically. Some souvenir shops in the tourist city of Rotorua,
which target chiefly at Asian tourists, have closed down because
of lack of customers.
</P>
<P>
Tourist companies now pin their hope on China, which designated
NZ as a tourist destination country for Chinese citizens. They are
urging the government to facilitate the entry into NZ by Chinese
tourists. But Tourism Minister Murray McCuily has warned that NZ
could not expect immediate benefit from the new Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
The international credit rating agency Moody's last week
downgraded the outlook of NZ's Aa1 rating from stable to negative.
Moody's said the adjustment reflected concerns over the increase
in NZ's current account deficit and the potential impact of events
in Asia on NZ's economy.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Treasury advised the cabinet last Monday
that the Asian crisis could cut NZ's growth forecast by about one
percentage point during the coming two years.
</P>
<P>
It also estimated the crisis could lop 300 million dollars (174
million US dollars) off the budget surplus for the next fiscal
year, putting the new round of tax cut promised by the government
in doubt.
</P>
<P>
However, the government still has confidence in Asia. Treasurer
 Winston Peters believes that NZ's economic future is still
bright.
</P>
<P>
He described last week the Asian crisis as "just one more
change in a global economy," saying Asia would recover from the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
He urged exporters not to abandon the Asian market.
</P>
<P>
His view seems to be shared by most NZ's businesses. Many of
them expressed cautiously optimistic and hoped the crisis could be
soon tided out. They also indicated their determination to stick
to the Asian market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
