<HEADLINE> Life Expectancy in Xinjiang Rises to 63 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The average life expectancy in
China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region has risen from 33 years
in the early 1950s to 63, according to a Saturday report in
People's Daily.
</P>
<P>
China's leading newspaper quoted a source from the region's
department of public health by saying that the increase could be
attributed to the establishment of a region-wide medical care
network.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Xinjiang now has more than 90,000
medical staff members in towns and 10,000 health workers in its
vast rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the established network and sufficient staff,
infectious diseases such as cholera, the plague and hepatitis are
now effectively prevented, said the report. 
</P>
