<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slight Output Rise Expected for Metal Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The metallurgical industry has
set a production target of 107 million tons of steel this year
while securing a net profit of 2.5 billion yuan (US$301 million),
said today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Zhang Shuliang, director of the iron and steel
production department with the Ministry of the Metallurgical
Industry, as saying that this year's focus is being shifted from
increasing quantity to quality upgrading, and the rise in profits
mainly will come from cutting costs and turning around more than 12
money-losing companies.
</P>
<P>
Low profit margin last year was widely blamed on falling steel
prices and an upswing of energy costs. "Such a situation forced us
to rely on ourselves to explore profit potential," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
The money-losing companies can expect to make profit this year
by separating subsidiary branches from the main manufacturing
plants. In this way, Anshan Steel Group slashed its deficit by 200
million yuan (US$24.1 million) last year after splitting from its
nine affiliates.
</P>
<P>
"The companies should make efforts to slash energy costs as
much as possible," Zhang said, adding that the industry will save
one billion yuan (US $120 million) a year when it buys 100 million
tons of coal after the price was bargained down 10 yuan (US$1.21)
per ton.
</P>
<P>
He urged companies to bid to obtain the lowest purchase price.
</P>
<P>
Zhang also encouraged the good-performance companies to raise
more capital through the Chinese and foreign stock markets.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 17 large and medium-sized companies were listed,
raising 12.4 billion yuan (US$1.5 billion). About 16 companies
are expected to go public this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
