<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Australia's Constitutional Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The Constitutional Convention
beginning on Monday brought together 152 delegates at the Old
Parliament House for two weeks to debate whether Australia should
become a republic, and if so, what form the republic should take.
</P>
<P>
Half of the delegates to the convention were appointed by the
government including:
</P>
<P>
Twenty members of the federal parliament (12 from the
government, six opposition, one Australian Democrat and one
Independent);
</P>
<P>
Twenty state and territory MPs, (three from each of the six
state and one each from the Australian Capital Territory and
Northern Territory);
</P>
<P>
Thirty-six community delegates representing Aborigines, young
people and other organizations.
</P>
<P>
The other half were elected in a voluntary postal ballot
conducted in December last year.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, 46 of the elected have declared themselves to be in
favor of a republic, 27 are monarchists and three have not
publicly declared their position.
</P>
<P>
The convention opened by chairman Ian Sinclair in the House of
Representatives chamber in the Old Parliament House, followed by
addresses from Prime Minister John Howard and Opposition leader
Kim Beazley.
</P>
<P>
The convention will run from Monday (February 2) to Friday
(February 6), and Monday (February 9) to Friday (February 13).
</P>
<P>
The conference will first debate the question "Whether
Australia should become a republic", but the bulk of proceedings
will be taken up with determining "Which model for an Australian
republic might be put to the Australian people in a vote?"
</P>
<P>
Final votes on these questions will be taken on the last two
days of the convention before the presentation of the final
communique to Prime Minister John Howard.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister wants the convention to come up with a clear
republican alternative, which can then be decided in a referendum
in time for a change by the centenary of federation in 2001, while
the republicans hope to have an Australian president, not the
Governor-General, to open the Olympic Games in 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
