<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Historic Constitutional Convention Starts in Canberra </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- A historic convention to
discuss whether Australia should become a republic begins in
Canberra Monday morning, Although the convention will not decide
the forthcoming system, but it gets the republic wheel moving
again.
</P>
<P>
The 152 delegates - half appointed and the other half elected
by popular ballot - meet in the old Parliament House over the next
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Republicans have a clear majority of the elected delegates, but
are split over whether a republic should have an elected head of
state, or one appointed by the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Australians for a Constitutional Monarchy (ACM) executive
director Kerry Jones said that "it is the republicans' job to tell
us what they want to change so they have got to sort out their
differences and tell us what models they are prepared to face up
to."
</P>
<P>
Australian Republican Movement (ARM) chairman Malcolm Turnbull,
who favors a president chosen by the parliament, said it was
essential republicans work together.
</P>
<P>
"We feel we are getting very close to the time when a
referendum will be put to the Australian people," he said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The opening addresses will be given by Prime Minister John
Howard, Opposition Leader Kim Beazley, Turnbull and ACM National
Convener LLoyd Waddy.
</P>
<P>
However, the bulk of the convention will be taken up with
debating when Australia should become a republic, what would be
needed to bring about the change and what form the republic should
take. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
