<HEADLINE> UK Reaffirms Readiness to Use Force Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The British government today
reaffirmed its readiness to use force against Iraq while the
U.N.-Iraq standoff on arms inspection continued worsening.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a BBC television interview today, British Defense
Secretary George Robertson refused to rule out the use of force,
but he was reluctant to elaborate the concrete military options
which were under consideration.
</P>
<P>
However, Robertson made it clear that "there is absolute
resolution that if he (Saddam) is not willing to comply with the
UN Security Council resolutions, then force is an option, and an
option that will in extremes be used."
</P>
<P>
"If the United Nations is flouted, if the will of the world
community is flouted, if Saddam continued to have these dreadful
weapons of mass destruction, then what future for the Middle East,
for the Gulf Region?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
"That is the question that can only be answered by the fact
that we have to show resolution. There is no option," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saraf has reportedly
criticized British Prime Minister Tony Blair for calling Saddam an
"evil dictator."
</P>
<P>
Saraf noted that Blair had used "cheap adjectives" to describe
Iraqi leader Saddam, but Downing Streets sources refused this
evening to retract Blair's warning by saying "the Prime Minister's
remarks stand." 
</P>
